olds","36590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517418","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>In 2012, DECC published an ‘Assessment of advanced reactor systems against UK performance metrics’, which it had commissioned from the National Nuclear Laboratory. This analysis covered molten salt reactors.</p><p> </p><p>These can be found online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/65502/6299-assessment-reactor-systems-uk-metrics.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/65502/6299-assessment-reactor-systems-uk-metrics.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/65503/6302-addendum-assessment-reactor-metrics.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/65503/6302-addendum-assessment-reactor-metrics.pdf</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:50:04.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517418/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517418/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what information her Department holds on the viability of molten salt reactors to generate electricity.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","36622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517420","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>Under the 2009 Renewable Energy Directive the UK has a target to deliver 15% of its energy from renewable sources by 2020. The government recognises that solar thermal can contribute towards the attainment of the renewable energy target. In 2014, renewable heat provided 2730 tonnes of oil equivalent, around 20% of total renewable energy. Around 2% of renewable heat came from solar thermal.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em></p><p><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-sources-of-energy-chapter-6-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-sources-of-energy-chapter-6-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes</a></em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:56:20.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517420/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517420/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Heating: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her policy is on the role of solar thermal technologies in meeting the UK's renewable heat targets.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","36522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517421","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-10","<p>Any measure which reduces the energy costs faced by a fuel poor home will have a beneficial impact on tackling fuel poverty. However, in order to tackle fuel poverty most cost effectively, it is right to focus on measures that can yield the greatest reductions in energy needs at least cost.</p><p> </p><p>For example, low cost insulation is typically more cost effective in improving the energy efficiency of fuel poor homes than other measures, including solar thermal.</p><p> </p><p>That is why Government is committed to insulating 1m homes this Parliament, helping to tackle the root cause of fuel poverty through cost effective policy.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-10T15:46:53.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517421/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517421/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Heating: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the potential of solar thermal hot water heating to tackle fuel poverty.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","36521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517422","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-10","<p>The number of F and G-rated fuel poor households [1] in England that will be in receipt of Warm Home Discount to 2020 will depend on changes in the energy efficiency of the housing stock and reforms to the welfare system over time.</p><p> </p><p>Based on current scheme eligibility, we estimate that around 25% of F and G-rated fuel poor households in England are eligible for Warm Home Discount.</p><p> </p><p>The Warm Home Discount has an important role in supporting households with their energy bills but is not the primary way we are addressing fuel poverty in the long term. We are reforming the Energy Company Obligation to improve the energy efficiency of homes that need it most, tackling the root cause of fuel poverty.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> As measured by the Fuel Poverty Energy Efficiency Rating. More information is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/332236/fpeer_methodology.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/332236/fpeer_methodology.pdf</a> </em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-10T15:48:07.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517422/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517422/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 27 April 2016 to Question 35137, what estimate she has made of the proportion of fuel poor households needed to reach the interim energy efficiency target of EPC band E by 2020 using the fuel poverty efficiency rating methodology that will be households in receipt of the Warm Homes Discount Scheme.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","36488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517423","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-12","<p>I refer the rt. hon. Member to the answer given to him by my hon. Friend the Minister of State for Food, Environment and Rural Affairs today to Question 35061:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-04-21/35061/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-04-21/35061/</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-12T11:03:15.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517423/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517423/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of dairy products procured for her Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517424","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Government’s recent consultation on reform of the Renewable Heat Incentive included a proposal to withdraw RHI support for solar thermal technologies. The consultation closed on 27 April. In taking a decision on the future of support for solar thermal we will consider all relevant factors including potential effects on the UK supply chain.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:57:20.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517424/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517424/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the proposed removal of Government support for solar thermal energy on the (a) UK solar thermal and (b) solar cylinder manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","36523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517425","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>EDF and the French Government have agreed a way forward on financing of the company. The chairman of EDF has begun a non-binding consultation with the company council ahead of a final investment decision, which is a commercial matter for EDF. The British Government and EDF are both confident that Hinkley will go ahead. The French Government also remain fully committed to the project.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:55:47.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517425/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517425/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the proposals of the French government to sell assets to raise capital to fund Hinkley Point C on the viability of that project.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","36544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517426","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>All Civil Nuclear Constabulary police officers are required to be Authorised Firearms Officers. As such, officers undertake a number of tasks and must meet fitness and capability standards which have been set by the College of Policing regardless of age or gender.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:54:09.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517426/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517426/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Civil Nuclear Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what duties officers of the Civil Nuclear Constabulary who reach 50 years of age in service are expected to perform under their contracts.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517427","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department actively engages with other Government departments, including at ministerial level, on a range of interdepartmental groups engaged in reducing emissions from heating and working towards our renewable energy targets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-12T11:05:44.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517427/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517427/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Heating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has to establish a cross-government team on the deployment of renewable and low-carbon heating.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","36441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517428","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority has produced a strong package of provisional remedies which will help deliver a fair deal to all consumers. They build on action already taken by the Government to improve competition.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will take forward appropriate implementation of the remedies once the Competition and Markets Authority has finalised its recommendations which are due by June.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:56:53.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517428/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517428/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the recent proposals published by the Competition and Markets Authority on competition in the energy market on 22 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","36442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517429","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority regulates the offshore helicopter industry.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:55:15.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517429/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517429/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Offshore Industry: Helicopters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will bring forward proposals to give the Oil and Gas Authority powers to regulate commercial decisions in the offshore helicopter industry.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","36474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517430","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills are engaging with a range of stakeholders as the UK oil and gas workforce plan is developed.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:50:38.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517430/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517430/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Fossil Fuels: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has to consult trades unions for UK oil and gas workers on the development of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas's plan for the UK oil and gas workforce.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","36450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517431","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>We expect to publish the UK Oil and Gas Workforce plan shortly.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:52:07.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517431/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517431/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Fossil Fuels: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she expects the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas to publish its plan for the UK oil and gas workforce.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","36452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517432","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The membership of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas is:</p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Rt. Hon. Amber Rudd MP, DECC Secretary of State (Chair)</p></li><li><p>Rt. Hon. Oliver Letwin MP, Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster</p></li><li><p>Rt. Hon. Anna Soubry MP, Minister of State for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise</p></li><li><p>Damian Hinds MP, Exchequer Secretary</p></li><li><p>Rt. Hon. David Mundell MP, Secretary of State for Scotland</p></li><li><p>The Lord Price, Minister of State for Trade and Investment</p></li><li><p>Andrea Leadsom MP, Minister of State for Energy</p></li><li><p>Dr Andy Samuel, Chief Executive of the Oil and Gas Authority.</p></li></ul>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:53:25.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517432/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517432/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Oil and Gas Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will publish the membership of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","36453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517433","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The members of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas regularly meet with industry in their roles and use this to inform the group’s work.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:51:06.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517433/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517433/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Fossil Fuels: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, on what dates the Inter-Ministerial Group on Oil and Gas met representatives from that industry to discuss its plan for the UK oil and gas workforce.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","36451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517434","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-12","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-12T11:35:15.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517434/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517434/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","Agriculture: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on farmers in (a) Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross and (b) Scotland of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517435","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-10","<p>Updated scientific advice is expected from the International Council for the Exploration of the Sea at the end of June this year, which will provide the latest assessment. However, the overall estimated reductions of the EU bass measures for the main gear groups in the commercial sector are set out in the Table below (calculated for the UK fleet). These are estimates which take into account the effects of the initial six-month moratorium, related derogations and the subsequent monthly vessel catch limits.</p><p> </p><p>Those parts of the industry that use hook-and-line and fixed gillnets benefit from derogations in the form of higher monthly catch limits and a moratorium of two, rather than six, months.</p><p> </p><p>More in-depth analysis, also taking into account additional factors such as the effects of the 2015 increase in the minimum conservation reference size for bass, and reduced availability, will be undertaken.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Gear type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Previous average tonnage, 2011-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated tonnage catch potential for 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated reduction from 2011-13 average (%)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bottom Trawl</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nets</p></td><td><p>378</p></td><td><p>224</p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hook and line</p></td><td><p>171</p></td><td><p>167</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Purse seine</p></td><td><p>56</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>63</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>pelagic trawl</p></td><td><p>77</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Totals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>813</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>460</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>43</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Table. Estimated reductions in catch potential for UK bass stocks (%).</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-10T15:57:15.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517435/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517435/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","White Fish","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what has been the change in sea bass stocks available to the UK fishing industry since the Council of European Fisheries Ministers meeting in 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","36537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517436","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Government has received two applications for emergency authorisation of neonicotinoid seed treatments for use on oilseed rape during 2016. These applications are currently being assessed according to the normal rules, which allow for limited and controlled use of a pesticide on an exceptional basis in emergency situations to control a danger which cannot be contained by any other reasonable means.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on whether or not to grant the authorisations will be made on the basis of an examination, by the UK Expert Committee on Pesticides, the Health and Safety Executive and Defra’s Chief Scientific Adviser, of the technical and scientific information submitted by the applicant.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-10T16:03:43.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517436/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517436/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to refuse the applications to use neonicotinoid pesticides on British fields this year.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","36571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>The UK has not specifically raised the issue of political prisoners. Our Embassy in Tel Aviv have raised concerns around detention, including Israel’s extensive use of administrative detention. Administrative detention should, according to international law, be used only when security makes it absolutely necessary rather than as routine practice, and as a preventative rather than a punitive measure. On 24 February, our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised the issue of administrative detention with the Israeli authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T16:03:46.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517437/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Israel: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions the Government has had with the government of Israel on political prisoners.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","36594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517438","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>Our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised our concerns about Susiya with the Israeli authorities on 21 January. More broadly, we regularly voice our opposition to the increase in demolitions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories with the Israeli Government, most recently on 21 April. In regards to demolitions of Bedouin villages in green-line Israel such as Umm al-Hiran, we believe a solution must respect the equality of all Israel’s citizens.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T16:02:52.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517438/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517438/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 35490, if he will raise the issue of the demolition of the villages of Susiya and Umm al-Hiran with the Israeli government.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","36591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517439","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>No date has yet been set for a decision. The Government is still considering its policy in this area and will announce developments to Parliament and the public in due course.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-09T13:38:13.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517439/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517439/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the Government will announce the decision on the resettlement of the Chagos Islanders.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","36592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517440","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-10","<p>Investment protection provisions in trade and investment treaties such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) aim to protect international investors from discriminatory or unfair treatment by a state. Their investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) provisions allow international investors to bring claims if they think the obligations set out in the treaty have been breached by the host state. As such, Governments cannot initiate claims against investors. Under the European Commission’s proposals for TTIP, in line with normal investment treaty practice, UK investors would be able to bring ISDS claims against the US Government.</p><p>The jurisdiction of any ISDS tribunal established in TTIP will be set out in the investment protection and ISDS provisions of the agreement. The aim of the European Commission’s proposals for investment protection provisions in TTIP is to clearly define the scope for ISDS claims and tribunal jurisdiction, including protecting the right of governments to regulate lawfully in the public interest. If an ISDS tribunal did exceed its jurisdiction in making an award, typically those elements of the resulting award would not be enforceable.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","36501","2016-05-10T11:17:15.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517440/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517440/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-04","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what provisions are in place to ensure that the jurisdiction of Investor State Dispute Settlement tribunal hearings remains restricted to its current mandate under the terms of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","36540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517441","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Government regards the Tibet Autonomous Region as part of the People’s Republic of China. We do have concerns about rights and freedoms in Tibet. We urge the Chinese authorities to respect freedom of religion, expression and association in Tibet in line with China’s constitution and the international frameworks to which it is a party.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:25:55.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517441/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517441/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Tibet: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to Freedom in the World 2016, published by Freedom House in January 2016, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the finding that Tibet is the second least free country in the world.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517442","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>Allegations of extra-judicial killings in Bangladesh are deeply concerning. We follow progress closely and raise concerns where there are credible allegations. We take human rights in Bangladesh seriously, naming it as one of 30 Human Rights Priority Countries in this year’s Foreign and Commonwealth Office Human Rights and Democracy report. In my speech during a House of Commons debate on the future of Bangladesh in June 2015 I reiterated our call for the Bangladesh Government to hold the perpetrators to account through impartial, transparent investigations.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:18:31.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517442/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517442/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Bangladesh: Assassination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Bangladesh on the increase in and alleged official toleration of extra-judicial killings in that country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","36570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517443","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>In addition to our UK-China Human Rights Dialogues, we continue to make our views on Tibet known to the Chinese authorities through various channels. In June 2015 and November 2015 I set out to Parliament our concerns about rights and freedoms in the Tibetan Autonomous Region. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy also covers these issues.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:21:45.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517443/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517443/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Tibet: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, on what occasions ministers of his Department raised the issue of Tibet during visits to China since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517444","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","The 22nd round of the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue was held in Beijing on 21-22 April 2015. It provided for detailed, expert engagement on a wide range of human rights concerns, resulting in a frank exchange of views. Our current assessment of the human rights situation in China can be seen in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:20:07.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517444/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517444/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","China: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the outcome of the last round of the UK-China human rights dialogue; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517445","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has not made an assessment of the expansion of China’s railway network in the Tibet Autonomous Region of China. We collect information about developments in Tibet from a wide range of reports, such as those made by the Chinese authorities and by Non-Governmental Organisations.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:15:54.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517445/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517445/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Tibet: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential consequences for native Tibetans of the planned railway expansion from China into Tibet.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517446","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>On 29 October 2008, the then Foreign Secretary (David Miliband) clarified the Government’s position on Tibet to the House, stating that: ‘our interest is in long-term stability, which can only be achieved through respect for human rights and greater autonomy for the Tibetans’. That remains the view of this Government. For our assessment of the current human rights situation in China, including Tibet, I refer the Hon. Member to the 2015 Foreign and Commonwealth Office Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy, published on 21 April.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:09:56.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517446/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517446/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Tibet: Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what benefits for Tibet have been achieved by the change of the Government's position on its status.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517447","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) publishes the number of UK FCO officials overseas in its Annual Report. In the financial year 2014/15 there were 114 UK FCO officials based in China and in the financial year 2010/11 there were 113 UK FCO officials based in China. Information prior to 2010 is not held in a way that enables us to accurately report the staffing position overseas.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-10T14:05:00.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517447/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517447/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","China: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK officials are based in China; and how many were based in that country in (a) 2010, (b) 2005 and (c) 1997.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","36575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517448","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-10","<p>The European Commission conducts trade negotiations – including the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) – on behalf of the EU and its Member States. In the UK, the Department, for Business, Innovation and Skills has the lead policy responsibility for TTIP. Ministers and officials are in regular formal and informal contact with officials from the European Commission, EU Member States and US, as we work to secure an agreement that benefits UK businesses, workers and consumers. This includes discussions with negotiators, legislators, administrations, and various other stakeholders from the EU and US.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-10T11:18:22.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517448/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517448/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-04","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what role his Department has played in the negotiation of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP); and what negotiations on TTIP he has attended as a representative of the Government.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","36545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517449","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>For the financial year 2015/6, 84% of dairy products (by value) procured as part of the UK contracted catering service in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office were sourced from British producers.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-05-10T16:33:17.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517449/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517449/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of dairy products procured for his Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517450","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-10","<p>Investment protection provisions in trade and investment treaties such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) aim to protect international investors from discriminatory or unfair treatment by a state. Their investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) provisions allow international investors to bring claims if they think the obligations set out in the treaty have been breached by the host state. As such, Governments cannot initiate claims against investors. Under the European Commission’s proposals for TTIP, in line with normal investment treaty practice, UK investors would be able to bring ISDS claims against the US Government.</p><p>The jurisdiction of any ISDS tribunal established in TTIP will be set out in the investment protection and ISDS provisions of the agreement. The aim of the European Commission’s proposals for investment protection provisions in TTIP is to clearly define the scope for ISDS claims and tribunal jurisdiction, including protecting the right of governments to regulate lawfully in the public interest. If an ISDS tribunal did exceed its jurisdiction in making an award, typically those elements of the resulting award would not be enforceable.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","36540","2016-05-10T11:17:15.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517450/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517450/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-04","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether (a) the Government will be able to bring cases to Investor State Dispute Settlements tribunals and (b) UK companies will be able to instigate actions against the US administration through such tribunals under the current terms of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","36501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517451","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>We are concerned by reports of recurrent clashes involving pastoralists and local farmers over land, farming rights, grazing routes and access to water in Nigeria, in particular in the centre of the country. We continue to call on all parties to find a peaceful solution to the underlying causes of these incidents, and welcome President Buhari’s commitment to prioritise ending these attacks.</p><p>The Department for International Development’s £39 million Nigeria Stability and Reconciliation Programme (NSRP) supports a range of initiatives across Nigeria to reduce conflicts and build bridges between communities. These include programmes that bring cattle herder and farming communities together to reduce conflict and agree rules for land and water use.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-10T13:10:42.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517451/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517451/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Nigeria: Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to encourage Nigeria to tackle Fulani militia attacks on non-Muslim villagers in the central Nigeria states of Plateau, Kaduna, Bauchi, Taraba and Benue; and whether the Government has offered any assistance to people displaced by ongoing violence in Agatu in the state of Benue.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","36520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517452","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>We are concerned by reports of recurrent clashes involving pastoralists and local farmers over land, farming rights, grazing routes and access to water in Nigeria, in particular in the centre of the country. We continue to call on all parties to find a peaceful solution to the underlying causes of these incidents.</p><p>Boko Haram is known to cooperate with criminal gangs and use illicit networks to facilitate the movement of weapons and persons in the region. However, we have no evidence that Boko Haram is involved in these violent clashes.</p><p>Together with international partners, we will continue supporting Nigeria, and its neighbours to tackle threats to regional stability.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-10T13:09:34.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517452/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517452/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Nigeria: Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of a possible relationship between the activities of Boko Haram and those of armed Fulani herders in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","36519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517453","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>As one of the Co-Convenors of the proposed Conference on a Middle East Weapons of Mass Destruction Free Zone, the British Government fully supports work towards such a Zone. We support the convening of a Conference as soon as possible, once the states of the region reach agreement on Conference arrangements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:59:33.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517453/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517453/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Middle East: Weapons of Mass Destruction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his policy is on the proposed international conference on a Middle East weapons of mass destruction free zone.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","36428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517454","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>Reductions in US and Russian nuclear forces have been negotiated directly between those two countries. Officials regularly discuss the implementation of those agreements, including the Intermediate Nuclear Forces agreement, with the US and other NATO partners. Nuclear weapons were not discussed at the meeting of the NATO/Russia Council held on 20 April 2016, which mainly focussed on the situation in Ukraine.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T16:01:09.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517454/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517454/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) other NATO member states and (b) Russia on bilateral reductions in stockpiles of non-strategic nuclear weapons; and whether such reductions were discussed at the meeting of the NATO-Russia Council in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","36429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517455","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review restated that the Government sees entry into force of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and successful negotiations on a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty as key steps towards multilateral disarmament. While we cannot predict when other States will take the decisions necessary to achieve these goals, we continue to pursue both objectives, which were strongly supported in the G7 Foreign Ministers’ declaration at their meeting in Hiroshima.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:58:35.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517455/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517455/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the likelihood of (a) full ratification of the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test Ban Treaty and (b) the commencement of negotiations on the proposed Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","36427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517456","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>During the last 12 months we have continued to urge the eight remaining Annex II states who have not yet ratified the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty to do so. We have worked through the EU to promote the entry into force and universalisation of the Treaty. We made a statement and co-sponsored a resolution supporting the entry into force of the Treaty at the 70th Session of the UN General Assembly. The G7 Foreign Ministers’ declaration at their meeting in Hiroshima was clear that all states should sign and ratify the treaty without delay and without conditions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:55:54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517456/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517456/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to encourage (a) China, (b) Egypt, (c) India, (d) Iran, (e) Israel, (f) North Korea, (g) Pakistan and (h) the United States to ratify the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","36425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517457","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>The UK continues to push for the early start of negotiations, without preconditions, on a Fissile Material Cut off Treaty (FMCT) in the Conference on Disarmament (CD). In order to help unblock the current impasse, earlier this year we submitted a draft proposal to establish a formal working group and an associated programme of work for the duration of the CD’s 2016 session, which includes provision for FMCT issues to be included.</p><p>We also supported the resolution at last year's UN General Assembly First Committee on issues surrounding an FMCT and we continue to work with partners in the CD to press Pakistan to start negotiations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:57:30.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517457/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517457/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to facilitate the start of negotiations on the proposed Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","36426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517458","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-09","<p>Ending Child Early and Forced Marriage (CEFM) remains a high priority for the UK Government at home and overseas. The UK has demonstrated its leadership through co-hosting the first ever Girl Summit in 2014, which galvanized global action to end CEFM and Female Genital Mutilation (FGM). Following the Girl Summit 2014 the UK has continued its global leadership on ending CEFM, including through support for UN Resolutions and advocating for a separate target on ending CEFM within the Global Goals. The UK has supported campaigns and country-led Girl Summits through its overseas network, raising awareness of the impact of CEFM and ensuring global commitments translate into country-level action.</p><p>The UK has committed £36 million towards ending CEFM around the world. This includes support for the UN’s Joint Programme to End Child Marriage working in twelve high prevalence countries and for grassroots civil society organisations working to challenge this harmful social practice. Domestically, the UK Government’s Forced Marriage Unit provides support to British Nationals overseas affected by forced marriage.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-09T15:50:02.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517458/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517458/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-04","Forced Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to end forced marriage worldwide.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","36641"
