"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517464","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>There is no specific requirement to engage with local authorities in regards to applications to close a general practitioner (GP) surgery, however, NHS England consider any discussions the practice concerned has had with its existing patients about the matter and the views of other local GP practices who may be impacted.</p><p>Practices can apply to NHS England to temporarily halt new patient registrations if they are facing immediate challenges in providing patient services in order to give them the opportunity to take action to resolve these issues and so that they can continue to provide safe, good quality care to their existing patients.</p><p>When NHS England receives a request to formally close a GP practice list over a longer period, they consider both the impact on patients as well as on neighbouring practices and services to avoid displacing a problem elsewhere.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-09T15:54:58.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517464/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517464/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","General Practitioners: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what obligations NHS England - South (South East) have to consult local councils before closing a GP list.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","36495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517465","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The timetable for the release of medical records in clinical negligence cases is determined by the Pre Action Protocol for clinical negligence claims. This prescribes 40 days for the release of the records, or the ability to request an extension to that time.</p><p>The NHS Litigation Authority (NHSLA) works with National Health Service trusts to ensure prompt release of medical records and other information which will inform the outcome of a claim for compensation. Often expert evidence will be required to give conclusive evidence as to whether there was negligence and if so, whether that caused injury to the claimant. As claims are often resolved in-house by the NHSLA, any costs which arise as a result of delays in receiving medical records are not recorded separately as they will fall within overall administration costs.</p><p>46% of claims were resolved without payment of damages in 2014/15; however, as above, it is often necessary to obtain expert medical advice to determine whether compensation is due.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","36494 ; 36518","2016-05-10T14:14:15.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517465/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517465/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the costs to the NHS Litigation Authority of late release of medical records where those records reveal a case to be unfounded; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","36493"
