"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517528","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-10","<p>Statistics for assaults committed by prisoners by ethnicity are published in the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin (see table 3.6 in the following link)</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The Offender Management Statistics Quarterly prison population provides information on the prison population by ethnicity, (see table 1.4 in the link)</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015</a></p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-05-10T15:27:07.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517528/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517528/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many violent incidents per 100 prisoners were committed by prisoners of each ethnic group in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517529","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>The number and proportion of non-UK nationals, their ethnic groups and offences are detailed on the attached table and covers the period of 2015. The government has a longstanding policy to do everything possible to return foreign prisoners to their home country at the earliest opportunity. Offender management statistics, including FNOs, can be found at this link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-11T09:27:36.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517529/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517529/answer","36554 - Table.xls","36554 - Table.xls","Immediate Custodial Sentenced Admissions 2015","Immediate Custodial Sentenced Admissions 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517529/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Sentencing: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of non-UK nationals of which ethnic groups dealt with in courts were sent to prison for each offence in the last year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517530","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>In 2015, of defendants whose cases were completed in the magistrates’ courts, 14% went on to have a trial after first listing. Of those cases, the mean duration from date of first listing to date of trial was 67 days and the median duration was 61 days.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-11T16:03:28.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517530/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517530/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Magistrates' Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time is from first appearance to trial in magistrates' courts.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517531","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-10","<p>The requested information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-10T16:42:03.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517531/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517531/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Magistrates' Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average cost to the public purse was of (a) a district judge and (b) bench of magistrates hearing (i) a guilty plea case, (ii) a summary trial and (iii) an either-way trial in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517532","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>Any offender who is believed to have committed further offences whilst on licence is liable to be arrested and charged and, if convicted, given a further sentence. If the offence is serious, they can be remanded into custody until trial. Offenders on licence who are charged with further offences are also liable to be recalled, potentially to serve the rest of their sentence in prison, as they will be in breach of the requirement of their licence to be of good behaviour. If the offender is assessed as not presenting a risk of harm to the public they can be assessed as suitable for a shorter, fixed term recall. Those who have been charged with serious sexual or violent offences will not be considered suitable for a fixed term recall.</p><p>Such offenders can apply for re-release before their automatic re-release date. In the last five years two offenders in 2011, one in 2013 and two in 2015 applied for release. Three of these offenders were subsequently released.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-05-11T16:25:01.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517532/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517532/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders returned under fixed term recalls have (a) submitted requests to be re-released before the end of the 28 day period and (b) been granted re-release before the end of the 28 day period in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517533","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-05-11T15:16:02.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517533/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517533/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Pre-sentence Reports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) fast and (b) standard delivery pre-sentence reports were prepared for offenders with (i) no, (ii) one to 14, (iii) 15 to 49, (iv) 50 to 99 and (v) 100 or more previous convictions in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517534","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Figures which detail the origin of dairy products are not held by my Department.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-05-12T09:57:22.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517534/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517534/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-05-04","Northern Ireland Office: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what proportion of dairy products procured for her Department was sourced from Northern Irish producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517535","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Civil Nuclear Constabulary and territorial police forces offer mutual support through individual agreements. It would not be appropriate to comment further on operational plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-11T10:57:50.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517535/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517535/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-04","Civil Nuclear Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will publish Government plans to enable officers of the Civil Nuclear Constabulary to attend incidents requiring an armed response in support of territorial police forces.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517536","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the hon Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-11T10:28:00.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517536/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517536/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Banks: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Financial Conduct Authority takes to ensure the chairs and boards of directors of banks adhere to commitments made within their published customer charters.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517537","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Civil Nuclear Constabulary and territorial police forces offer mutual support through individual agreements. As the Prime Minister said in his statement to the House of Commons on 23 November [23 Nov 2015: Column 1051], plans are in place to enable military personnel to support the Police in the event of major terrorist incidents in the UK. Military personnel will be able to fill a number of operational tasks. For national security reasons, it would not be appropriate for me to comment further on these detailed operational agreements.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-05-12T08:53:48.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517537/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517537/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-04","Civil Nuclear Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish Government plans to deploy armed officers from the Civil Nuclear Constabulary to support territorial police forces and to use the military to backfill such officers in civil nuclear establishments.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517538","Scotland Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Scotland Office has no in-house catering services and does not separately record the purchase of dairy products.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-05-11T11:43:52.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517538/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517538/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-05-04","Scotland Office: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what proportion of dairy products procured for his Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517539","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>My department follows the Government Buying Standard for food and catering to be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418072/gbs-food-catering-march2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418072/gbs-food-catering-march2015.pdf</a>. This specifies that any food purchased must conform as a minimum to UK statutory animal welfare standards or equivalent. The table below provides details on the proportion of dairy products that was sourced from British producers for the period 1<sup>st</sup> September 2014 to 31<sup>st</sup> August 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Agency Name</strong></p></td><td colspan="6"><p><strong>% of UK produced products</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Butter</p></td><td><p>Cheese</p></td><td><p>Cream</p></td><td><p>Milk</p></td><td><p>Yoghurt</p></td><td><p>All dairy</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfTC 2015* See note 1</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>81%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVSA 2015* See note 2</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>70%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>94%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVLA 2015* See note 3</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>88%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>94%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MCA &amp; VCA do not have onsite catering</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>DfTC note 1: Data covers the period 01/05/2015 to 31/08/2015. We have been unable to source data for DfTC pre May 2015 as we changed catering suppliers. All of the hard cheese and regional cheese provided are sourced from UK. There are number of non-indigenous, to UK, cheeses provided which are sourced from the EU. All of the butter, albeit a very minimal amount, is sourced from Republic of Ireland as the catering supplier is UK &amp; Ireland operating company and its current butter contract is with a producer in the Republic of Ireland.</p><p>DVSA note 2: Sample period 1st September 2014 to 31st August 2015.</p><p>DVLA note 3: Sample Period 1st Sept 2014 - 31st Aug 2015, butter portions originate from Republic of Ireland, all cream &amp; milk originates from Wales. All yoghurt originates from Denmark.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T08:45:17.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517539/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517539/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Department for Transport: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of dairy products procured for his Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517540","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>No such discussions have taken place. Helicopter operations in support of the offshore oil and gas sector are regulated by the Civil Aviation Authority and must comply with the safety requirements established by the European Aviation Safety Agency.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T10:41:31.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517540/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517540/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Offshore Industry: Helicopters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the safety of helicopter operations in the UK offshore oil and gas sector.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","36476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517541","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>We have already set out the minimum levels of service in the invitation to tender for East Anglia and where bidders see there is an opportunity to offer more than those, they can do so. That tends to be based on whether there is a commercial case for improving services further.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T08:02:59.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517541/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517541/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: Tendring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to ensure that the next East Anglia franchise provides more frequent train services to Clacton-on-Sea and Walton-on-the-Naze.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517542","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The impact of introducing the European Rail Traffic Management System is being evaluated first at the national level. Assessments for individual regions will be performed at a later stage.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T08:14:14.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517542/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517542/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","European Rail Traffic Management System: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of the European Rail Traffic Management System on rail services in East Anglia.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517543","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>In the invitation tender for the East Anglia franchise we have asked bidders to come forward with proposals to improve operational performance and passenger experience during times of disruption across all the franchise services.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T08:07:32.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517543/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517543/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: Tendring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to ensure that the next East Anglia franchise delivers greater punctuality and fewer cancellations on train services to Clacton-on-Sea and Walton-on-the-Naze.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517544","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The specification for the next franchise requires that bidders provide high quality rolling stock in their bids and 30% of the available quality points from the franchise evaluation (the highest level in any franchise) will be awarded for bidders’ plans for rolling stock improvements.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T10:19:57.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517544/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517544/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: Tendring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to ensure that the next East Anglia franchise introduces new rolling stock on routes to Clacton-on-Sea and Walton-on-the-Naze.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517545","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>I will announce the new East Anglia franchise operator in June, as planned.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T09:00:26.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517545/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517545/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","East Anglia Railway Line: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce the new East Anglia franchise operator.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517546","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Department is finalising the specification for the South Western franchise so that it offers the best possible proposition for passengers. I expect to issue the Invitation to Tender later this month.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T10:13:52.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517546/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517546/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","South West Railway Line: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the invitation to tender to be issued for the franchise currently held by South West trains.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","36604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517547","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The process for defining our priorities for investment in enhancements to the rail network - including in the Wessex area - for the funding period after March 2019 will start over the coming year taking into account the recommendations of the Bowe and Shaw reviews and the re-plan carried out by Sir Peter Hendy.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-10T09:43:19.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517547/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517547/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the funding available for capital projects in the Wessex area during Control Period 6 of the Network Rail plan.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","36603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517548","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>Fire safety regulations on London Underground are a matter for Transport for London (TfL), who have no plans to change them. TfL will continue to ensure that there are sufficient staff in place to maintain each London Underground station’s security, congestion, control and emergency plans, including adhering to minimum staffing levels where they exist.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T10:27:35.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517548/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517548/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","London Underground: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to change fire safety regulations governing staffing levels and other procedures on London Underground.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517549","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>As the DVLA website sits on the <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">Gov.uk</a> website, there was no cost associated with inserting a link to information on the <a href="http://eureferendum.gov.uk/" target="_blank">eureferendum.gov.uk</a> website.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-09T13:17:51.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517549/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517549/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-04","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the cost was of inserting the link to information on the EU referendum on the DVLA website.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517550","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Department’s Board Investment and Commercial Sub-Committee is chaired by the Permanent Secretary. Its membership consists of: the Directors General, the Directors for Corporate Finance, Group Finance, Analysis &amp; Strategy, Group Commercial Services, and Group Assurance; the Department’s Commercial Adviser; the Director of Legal; and the Lead Non-Executive Board Member. Other Non-Executive Board Members attend by invitation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T15:25:39.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517550/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517550/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Department for Transport: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the membership is of his Department's Board Investment and Commercial Sub Committee.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517551","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>An independent peer review of Network Rail’s renewals proposals, as referred to in Network Rail’s Board minutes of 24 February 2016, was conducted by Sotera Risk Solutions. The cost was £4,700 exclusive of Value Added Tax.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-09T15:32:33.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517551/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517551/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to Minute No. 16/20 of Network Rail's Board minutes of 24 February 2016, who carried out the third pay review of Network Rail's renewal proposals; and what was the cost of that review was to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517552","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>Fire safety regulations on London Underground are a matter for Transport for London (TfL). Under London Underground’s new staffing model introduced in April 2016, all London Underground stations continue to be staffed during traffic hours in line with the London Underground Rule Book – which includes defined minimum numbers of staff at sub-surface stations as required by the Fire Precautions (Sub-Surface Railway Stations) (England) Regulations 2009.</p><p> </p><p>The introduction of the new staffing model followed a review of individual stations’ Congestion Control and Emergency Plans, which identified various improvements to help maintain London Underground’s good safety record.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T09:57:01.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517552/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517552/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","London Underground: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment the Government has made of the adequacy of the fire safety regulations governing staffing levels and other procedures on London Underground.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517553","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>We expect Network Rail to deliver on our record investment in the rail network. In this case Network Rail is collaborating with Local Enterprise Partnerships to ensure the scheme is delivered.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-09T15:16:51.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517553/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517553/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: Market Harborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 36121, whether Network Rail plans to meet the full cost of the planned Market Harborough straightening works.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517554","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Department has regular meetings with Transport for London (TfL) where many issues are discussed, including passenger safety. This particular issue has not been discussed at recent meetings, but the Department has no reason to doubt that TfL is adhering to fire safety regulations on its services.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T10:10:37.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517554/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517554/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","London Underground: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with London Underground on fire safety regulations governing staffing levels and other procedures on those services.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517555","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>None. Fire safety regulations are a matter for Transport for London (TfL), who meet with the London Fire Brigade on a regular basis.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T10:24:08.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517555/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517555/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","London Underground: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with London Fire Brigade on fire safety regulations governing staffing levels and other procedures on London Underground.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517556","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>We do not hold this information.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T14:59:37.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517556/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517556/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Offshore Suppliers: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many UK seafarer (a) officers and (b) ratings employed in the offshore supply vessel sector have been made redundant in each month since June 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517557","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Air Accident Investigation Branch (AAIB) are assisting the Norwegian Safety Investigation Authority with an Accredited Representative and two advisors to the EC225 accident on 29 April. This is due to the death of a UK national on board the helicopter and previous experience with EC225 accidents in the North Sea. The AAIB also successfully downloaded the combined cockpit voice recorder and flight data recorder (black box) last weekend and have provided that information to the investigation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T10:38:29.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517557/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517557/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Helicopters: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons and in what roles Air Accident Investigation Branch officials are attending the scene of the fatal crash of an EC225L Super Puma helicopter on the south west coast of Norway on 29 April 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","36475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517558","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>Since January 2015, 11 offshore supply vessels have left the UK flag. Out of these 11 vessels, 10 have re-flagged under open registers. One left in January 2015; three in April 2015; two in May 2015; and one in each of June 2015, July 2015, November 2015 and March 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T14:51:05.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517558/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517558/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Offshore Suppliers: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many UK-registered offshore supply vessels have been re-flagged under open registers in each month since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517559","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>According to commercial world fleet data sourced from IHS Global Limited, there were two UK registered offshore vessels with a ‘laid-up’ status on 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p>We do not have any further data available for use on laid-up vessels since this time. The data is not in a format from which inactivity periods are readily obtainable.</p><p> </p><p>According to online vessel search engines, the last known ship positions for the two UK registered offshore vessels that were laid-up at the end of 2015 were Port Elizabeth (South Africa) on 24 August 2015 and Elefsis (near the Athens port of Piraeus, Greece) on 19 September 2015.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T14:56:48.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517559/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517559/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Offshore Suppliers: Aberdeen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many UK-registered offshore supply vessels (OSVs) have been laid up in Aberdeen port since January 2015; and what the average period of inactivity was for UK-registered OSVs (a) at that port and (b) in total during that period.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517560","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>United Nations Economic Commission for Europe Regulation No 10 seeks to limit the maximum emission of electromagnetic radiation from vehicles. Recognising the rapid changes in technology in new vehicles, the relevant UN-ECE technical committee has established a task force to consider the implications of new technologies such as those used by driverless vehicles.</p><p>The Department is participating in the work of the task force.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-09T16:08:46.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517560/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517560/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Driverless Vehicles: Electromagnetic Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 April 2016 to Question 34235, whether the UN Economic Commission for Europe Regulation 10 specifically covers the potential health risks of electromagnetic emissions by multiple driverless vehicles as well as those from single vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","36449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517561","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>In its Final Report the Airports Commission recommended that support for schools, including insulation of school buildings, should be a priority component of Heathrow Airport Limited’s community compensation package.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is continuing to consider the comprehensive evidence published by the Airports Commission before reaching a view on its preferred scheme. In December the Government announced that we are undertaking a package of further work on developing the best possible package of measures to mitigate the impacts of expansion on local communities. This work includes the impact on schools.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T14:23:19.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517561/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517561/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what account his Department has taken of the additional costs of insulating and ventilating schools and hospitals affected by the new flightpaths of a third runway in estimating the cost of a third runway at Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","36423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517562","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>All of the promoters have proposed privately-funded schemes, and as privately-owned companies we expect airports to fund the development of new airport capacity fully.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T14:42:34.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517562/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517562/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to source additional funding for any shortfall in  funding between what Heathrow Airport Limited commits to pay for a third runway and the estimated cost.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","36424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517563","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Fourth Railway Package has no impact on this provision of domestic primary legislation, which prohibits the award of passenger rail franchises to public sector operators. The EU legislation would not itself prohibit awards to public service operators if in future the domestic prohibition were removed. Similarly, section 30 of the Railways Act 1993, which puts the franchising authority under a duty to secure the continuity of services – including by directly operating the services – will continue to apply.</p><p> </p><p>The current text of the Fourth Railway Package permits direct awards, including to public sector operators, in a range of circumstances including where they can be justified by the characteristics of the network and potential benefits to passengers.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-10T08:49:49.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517563/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517563/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railways: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the potential effect of the latest version of the Fourth Railway Package would be on the ability of his Department to directly award passenger service contracts to public sector operators, as defined by section 25(1) of the Railways Act 1993.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517564","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>This work is focused on options for making the commercial functions of the MCA, such as the UK Ship Register, more attractive. An initial review of these options is expected to be completed by the autumn and will be published.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T16:20:44.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517564/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517564/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the outcome of the current review of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's (a) status and (b) governance; and if he will ensure that a copy of that review is placed in the Library when it is complete.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517565","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) authorise the following six classification societies to act as Recognised Organisations (ROs) for the survey and inspection of UK registered convention size ships. These are: American Bureau of Shipping; Bureau Veritas; ClassNK; DNV GL AS; Lloyd’s Register; and RINA.</p><p> </p><p>The one change within the past 5 years to the list of authorised ROs was in 2015 following the merger of Det Norske Veritas and Germanischer Lloyd to become DNV GL AS. The MCA separately authorised both of these organisations as ROs prior to their merger.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T16:24:30.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517565/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517565/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Shipping: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Recognised Organisations for the purposes of survey and inspection of international shipping were certified by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517566","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p><strong> </strong>There are no projected savings from the Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA) proposals to close Norwich Marine Office because the plan put forward proposes to invest in a Marine Office nearer London.</p><p> </p><p>Just closing the office would realise savings of £66K per annum. The only value to the MCA is the value of the lease. The value of land and building assets reside with the landlord.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T16:28:58.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517566/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517566/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Norwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what projection he has made of the cost savings from the proposed closure of the Marine Office in Norwich in 2019.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517567","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>No members of staff have been seconded from the private sector to work on the implementation of these recommendations at this stage. Both the Department and the MCA engage closely and regularly with industry partners.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T16:31:54.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517567/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517567/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Department for Transport: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff in (a) his Department and (b) the Maritime and Coastguard Agency have been seconded from the private sector to work on the implementation of the recommendations of the (i) Maritime Growth Study and (ii) UK Ship Register Advisory Panel.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517568","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>All links to the <a href="http://eureferendum.gov.uk/" target="_blank">eureferendum.gov.uk</a> website will be removed from government channels such as <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> at the start of the 28 day restricted period ahead of the EU Referendum.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-09T13:18:28.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517568/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517568/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-04","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the link on the DVLA website to information on the EU referendum will be removed when the purdah period comes into force.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","36620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517569","Wales Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Wales Office does not procure any dairy products.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-05-11T11:26:37.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517569/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517569/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-05-04","Wales Office: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of dairy products procured for his Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517570","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>Since 1998 the Department for Work and Pensions occupies space provided through a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME Contract.</p><p> </p><p>Under the terms of this PFI Contract the Department leases fully serviced accommodation from our private sector partner Telereal Trillium. This Contract provides a variety of facility management services which include catering services.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of dairy products procured by Telereal Trillium for resale in staff restaurants and retail outlets sourced from British producers for the period January – March 2016 is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>DWP Dairy Jan-March 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dairy Sub-Category</p></td><td><p>Total Spend</p></td><td><p>UK Sourced</p></td><td><p>British %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Milk</p></td><td><p>£36,347.37</p></td><td><p>£36,347.37</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheese</p></td><td><p>£24,494.74</p></td><td><p>£15,181.69</p></td><td><p>62%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yoghurt</p></td><td><p>£5,406.24</p></td><td><p>£5,406.24</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Butter</p></td><td><p>£4,468.50</p></td><td><p>0.00</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cream</p></td><td><p>£1,318.58</p></td><td><p>£994.84</p></td><td><p>75%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Cheese 62% - A number of non–indigenous cheese lines are procured from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Butter 0% - Spend on butter is low and it is sourced from Ireland</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T15:35:52.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517570/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517570/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of dairy products procured for his Department was sourced from British producers in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","36515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517571","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>In conjunction with the Department for Communities and Local Government, the Department for Work and Pensions has recently conducted an evidence-based review of supported accommodation in GB and we expect to publish the report shortly. Alongside this work, as part of our policy review, we will continue to work with and listen to all relevant stakeholders, including the supported housing sector in order to develop a workable and sustainable funding regime.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T09:15:54.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517571/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517571/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to publish its response to its public consultation on housing benefit reform and supported housing.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","36529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517572","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>We recognise the importance of assessing the potential impact on specialist homes. However, as the policy is not yet fully developed we are unable to provide any Information relating to this at this time.</p><p> </p><p>For this reason on 1 March 2016 we announced, via a Written Ministerial Statement, that the effect of the LHA cap for those living in social sector supported housing would be deferred by a year, pending the outcome of a review, This means that the measure will only effect those who have taken on or renewed a tenancy from April 2017 rather than April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We have done this because we understand the importance of ensuring that both those living in supported housing and those who provide this type of accommodation receive appropriate protections. This is why we are awaiting the outcome of a “Supported Accommodation” research project and subsequent policy review, to ensure support is focused on the most vulnerable and appropriate groups are safeguarded.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T09:05:22.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517572/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517572/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of capping housing benefit to the same level as local housing allowance on the number of specialist homes in (a) Sunderland, (b) the North East, and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","36530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517573","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>All Health Professionals (HPs) undertaking assessments on behalf of DWP must be registered practitioners who have also met requirements around training, experience and competence.</p><p> </p><p>Approval to work as an HP must be conferred by the DWP Chief Medical Adviser on behalf of the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.</p><p> </p><p>For the delivery of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) assessments, they must be an occupational therapist, level 1 nurse, physiotherapist, paramedic or doctor. They must also be fully registered and have at least two years’ post full-registration experience.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to their profession, the Department recognises the importance of ensuring that individuals also have sufficient experience, skills and training to carry out their duties and PIP providers are required to ensure that the HPs carrying out assessments have knowledge of the clinical aspects and likely functional effects of a wide range of health conditions and impairments. This means that all HPs receive comprehensive training in disability analysis which includes a functional evaluation as to how medical conditions and the long-term medical treatment of those conditions affect an individual’s ability to perform day-to-day activities. Prior to carrying out an assessment the HP routinely refreshes their knowledge of any condition with which they are not fully familiar.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-09T15:44:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517573/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517573/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria his Department has set to ensure that people who carry out personal independence payment assessments for Capita are fully qualified medically.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","36632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517574","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-09T15:34:14.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517574/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517574/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Social Rented Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016, to Question 35962, what estimate he has made of the number of tenants with spare rooms who have moved to smaller accommodation following removal of the subsidy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","36585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517575","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>On 1 March 2016 we announced, via a Written Ministerial Statement, that the effect of the LHA cap for those living in social sector supported housing would be deferred by a year, pending the outcome of a review, This means that the measure will only effect those who have taken on or renewed a tenancy from April 2017 rather than April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We have done this because we understand the importance of ensuring that both those living in supported housing and those who provide this type of accommodation receive appropriate protections. This is why we are awaiting the outcome of a “Supported Accommodation” research project and subsequent policy review, to ensure support is focused on the most vulnerable and appropriate groups are safeguarded.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T09:12:57.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517575/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517575/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department is taking steps to provide support for people living in supported housing who will be affected by the cap of housing benefit at the same level as local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","36580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517576","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>Decision Makers considering the imposition of a sanction are DWP employees. When a sanctionable failure is identified by a work coach, a referral is made which is randomly assigned to a centralised decision maker to review the circumstances of the case, including any representations from the claimant regarding good reason for non-compliance, and arrive at a decision independently of the work coach.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-09T10:31:09.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517576/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517576/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35960, on universal credit, who the independent decision makers will be; and how those people will be appointed.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","36595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517577","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>In some cases, where a claimant would be excluded from work related requirements they will be excluded from the pool of “qualifying claimants”. They will also cease to be part of the scheme if the same circumstances apply after they have been selected. These are:</p><p> </p><ul><li>recent victims of domestic violence;</li><li>claimants who provide medical evidence of unfitness for work pending a work capability assessment;</li><li>prisoners;</li><li>claimants absent from GB for medical treatment etc;</li><li>claimants suffering a bereavement;</li><li>claimants undergoing treatment for drug or alcohol addiction.</li></ul>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-09T10:35:49.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517577/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517577/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35960, on universal credit, what the exclusion criteria are.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","36596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517578","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Government Social Research code is publicly available online: <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20150922160821/http:/www.civilservice.gov.uk/networks/gsr/gsr-code" target="_blank"><strong>http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20150922160821/http://www.civilservice.gov.uk/networks/gsr/gsr-code</strong></a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-09T15:39:13.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517578/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517578/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35959, if he will publish the Government Social Research Code.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","36597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517579","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>Automatic enrolment is the cornerstone of this Government’s private pension reforms, normalising pension saving and reversing the decade long decline in pension savings prior to introduction in 2012. It has been a great success to date with over 6 million people enrolled and opt-outs low at around 10 per cent.</p><p> </p><p>The Lifetime ISA is not a part of the pension system but an additional flexible savings product that can complement pension saving but not replace it. Increasing the choice of savings products available, it aims to support the Government’s ambition to encourage a regular savings habit amongst young people and to create a culture of medium and long term saving at different points in people’s lives.</p><p> </p><p>The Budget 2016 Lifetime ISA costing, certified by the OBR, did not anticipate any revenue impact from individuals opting-out of their workplace pensions in order to save into Lifetime ISAs.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T15:13:55.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517579/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517579/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effects on auto enrolment of the roll-out of the lifetime ISA.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","36399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517580","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>Pension Wise provides free and impartial guidance to those aged 50 and over with a defined contribution pension to help them understand their options.</p><p> </p><p>It was announced at the 2015 summer budget that the age for eligibility would be lowered to 50. Pension Wise has developed new content for 50 – 54 year olds to make the guidance appointments more relevant to their needs and this is now live.</p><p> </p><p>The government plans to restructure the delivery of public financial guidance to ensure that all consumers can access the help they need when they need it.</p><p> </p><p>Pension Wise does not give specific advice on products or provider recommendations. There are currently no plans for Pension Wise to provide guidance on lifetime ISAs or Automatic Enrolment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T15:17:01.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517580/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517580/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to extend the Pensions Wise service to people (a) between 20 and 40 and (b) between 40 and 50; and if he will make that service available to advise people on whether to invest in a lifetime ISA or under auto enrolment.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","36400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517581","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-09","<p>Departmental decision makers have access to specific online guidance on Joint Hypermobility Syndrome that contains a link to the Ehlers - Danlos Support UK website.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-09T15:50:10.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517581/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517581/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Social Security Benefits: Ehlers-danlos Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what (a) medical and (b) other guidance his Department makes available to staff making decisions on benefit claims for people with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","36402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517582","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p><strong>Table 1: </strong>Estimated median annual earnings from self-employment (£) and total annual income from all sources (£) of all self-employed men and women from 2011/12 to 2013/14.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Annual earnings from self-employment (£)</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Total annual income (£)</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>Sample size (self-employed only)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>15,128</p></td><td><p>7,141</p></td><td><p>19,226</p></td><td><p>12,641</p></td><td><p>2,652</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>14,737</p></td><td><p>6,404</p></td><td><p>18,907</p></td><td><p>12,572</p></td><td><p>2,568</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>13,200</p></td><td><p>7,821</p></td><td><p>16,800</p></td><td><p>12,580</p></td><td><p>2,672</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Source:</strong> Family Resources Survey</p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ol><li>Figures have been adjusted to 2013/14 prices using CPI and are rounded to the nearest pound (£).</li></ol><ol start="2"><li>Self-employment is defined using the ILO definition.</li><li>Total annual income is the sum of income from all sources received by the individual, including earnings from all forms of employment, benefits and tax credits, private pensions and investments. This will include benefits and tax credits that are assessed at a benefit unit (or family) level.</li><li>The Family Resources Survey is a nationally representative sample of UK households.</li><li>The figures from the Family Resources Survey are based on a sample of households which have been adjusted for non-response using multi-purpose grossing factors which align the Family Resources Survey to former Government Office Region population by age and sex. Estimates based on survey data are subject to uncertainty due to sampling error and remaining non-response error.</li><li>Median self-employment income divides the number of people, when ranked by self-employment income, into two equal-sized groups.</li></ol><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-11T14:16:51.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517582/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517582/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-04","Self-employed: Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average annual income of self-employed (a) men and (b) women was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","36438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517583","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The development of Sustainability and Transformation Plans does not alter the existing statutory responsibilities of clinical commissioning groups, local authorities and NHS arms length bodies. Sustainability and Transformation Plans are designed to enable local health and care leaders to work together more collaboratively to help each other meet their statutory responsibilities more effectively and efficiently. They do not alter existing arrangements for accountability.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-10T13:00:10.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517583/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517583/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the governance arrangements put in place to oversee the development of Sustainability and Transformation Plans will ensure appropriate accountability to Parliament for decisions made.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517584","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) remain accountable for securing high-quality healthcare services for their local populations. In some areas, CCGs have established or are planning to establish collaborative commissioning arrangements across a number of CCGs and/or with local authorities, where they consider that this will help them improve quality and outcomes for their local population.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-10T14:45:26.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517584/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517584/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what form of delegation from Clinical Commissioning Groups is being made to ensure appropriate governance in relation to Sustainability and Transformation Plans.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517585","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>Where Sustainability and Transformation plans envisage changes to the way that NHS services are commissioned or delivered, it will be the responsibility of the relevant clinical commissioning groups to involve patients and the public in considering and making decisions on those proposals, in line with their duties under the National Health Service Act 2006.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL8179","2016-05-10T12:57:02.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517585/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517585/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what formal public consultation will need to take place before Sustainability and Transformation Plans are submitted to NHS England by 30 June.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517586","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>Where Sustainability and Transformation plans envisage changes to the way that NHS services are commissioned or delivered, it will be the responsibility of the relevant clinical commissioning groups to involve patients and the public in considering and making decisions on those proposals, in line with their duties under the National Health Service Act 2006.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL8178","2016-05-10T12:57:02.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517586/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517586/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what formal public consultation will need to take place when Sustainability and Transformation Plans are given approval by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517587","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The NHS Planning Guidance, published in December 2015, explained that the success of Sustainability and Transformation Plans will depend on having an open, engaging, and iterative process that harnesses the energies of clinicians, patients, carers, citizens, local authorities, health and wellbeing boards, and local community partners. Local authorities should be fully engaged in the development of all Sustainability and Transformation Plans. In some cases, local National Health Service organisations have agreed with local authorities that a senior council leader will lead the Sustainability and Transformation Plan for their area.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-10T12:55:33.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517587/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517587/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role local authorities will play in the development of Sustainability and Transformation Plans other than through membership of Health and Wellbeing Boards.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517588","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>As part of the essential services within the National Health Service community pharmacy contractual framework, all community pharmacies are expected to provide advice in respect to dispensed medicines, support for self-care, prescription linked healthy life style advice and signposting to others where the pharmacy cannot itself provide support. The volume of advice given by community pharmacists to patients that is not covered by a commissioned services contract has not been assessed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-11T15:55:47.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517588/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517588/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Pharmacy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the volume of advice given by community pharmacists to patients that is not covered by a commissioned services contract.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517589","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The European Development Fund (EDF) provides development assistance in accordance with the Cotonou Agreement. The 11<sup>th</sup> EDF resources are implemented in compliance with the principals of sound financial management and transparency. Every year the accounts of the EDF are scrutinised by the European Court of Auditors (ECA) who perform rigorous annual audits on the EU’s finances. The ECA also review specific programmes and projects for effectiveness and impact.</p><p>DFID regularly reviews the work of its partners, including the EU, to ensure that aid is being spent efficiently and appropriately.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-11T13:38:08.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517589/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517589/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-04","Cotonou Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the long-term protections in place for the monies granted under the Cotonou Convention in the 11th European Development Fund.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL8182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517590","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-12","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the noble Lord.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-05-12T11:54:20.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517590/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517590/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-04","Managers: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to legislate to introduce voting thresholds that empower shareholders in the operations of public companies in relation to executive pay.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517591","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Government is committed to the principle that people should have access to appropriate and accessible investment options and understand the charges that they face. We appreciate the efforts that industry have made to fulfil this aim.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is conducting a market study into asset management, where such issues fall under its scope. The FCA expect to publish an interim report in summer 2016 and a final report in early 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-05-11T16:13:14.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517591/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517591/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Woodford Investment Management","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the initiative at Woodford Investment Management to publish monthly all the costs that investors pay.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517592","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government is committed to the principle that people who have worked hard and saved should have access to appropriate and accessible investment options and understand the charges that they face. We appreciate the efforts that industry have made to fulfil this aim.</p><p> </p><p>Since last April, the Government has ensured that trustees of defined contribution pension schemes report charges levied on members in schemes used for auto enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>We are also engaging with international work on transparency, such as the legislation agreed at European Union level through the Packaged Retail and Insurance Based Investment Products (PRIIPs) and Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID). MiFID II will introduce new measures to increase transparency of research costs for clients of portfolio managers. Under these new measures, portfolio managers may only pay for research through their own funds or from a specific research payment account funded by its clients and subject to specific controls, including a research budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is also currently conducting a market study into asset management, which covers the issue of whether the level of fund management fees charged to consumers reflects a competitive market. We await the FCA’s assessment of competition in this sector. The FCA expect to publish an interim report in summer 2016 and a final report in early 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8186 ; HL8187 ; HL8188","2016-05-12T10:11:31.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517592/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517592/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Financial Services: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to take steps to encourage fund managers to take research costs out of their management fees, rather than deducting those costs through additional fees.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517593","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government is committed to the principle that people who have worked hard and saved should have access to appropriate and accessible investment options and understand the charges that they face. We appreciate the efforts that industry have made to fulfil this aim.</p><p> </p><p>Since last April, the Government has ensured that trustees of defined contribution pension schemes report charges levied on members in schemes used for auto enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>We are also engaging with international work on transparency, such as the legislation agreed at European Union level through the Packaged Retail and Insurance Based Investment Products (PRIIPs) and Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID). MiFID II will introduce new measures to increase transparency of research costs for clients of portfolio managers. Under these new measures, portfolio managers may only pay for research through their own funds or from a specific research payment account funded by its clients and subject to specific controls, including a research budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is also currently conducting a market study into asset management, which covers the issue of whether the level of fund management fees charged to consumers reflects a competitive market. We await the FCA’s assessment of competition in this sector. The FCA expect to publish an interim report in summer 2016 and a final report in early 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8185 ; HL8187 ; HL8188","2016-05-12T10:11:31.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517593/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517593/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Financial Services: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the level of fund management fees charged to consumers reflects a competitive market, in the light of the variable performance of such funds.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517594","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government is committed to the principle that people who have worked hard and saved should have access to appropriate and accessible investment options and understand the charges that they face. We appreciate the efforts that industry have made to fulfil this aim.</p><p> </p><p>Since last April, the Government has ensured that trustees of defined contribution pension schemes report charges levied on members in schemes used for auto enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>We are also engaging with international work on transparency, such as the legislation agreed at European Union level through the Packaged Retail and Insurance Based Investment Products (PRIIPs) and Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID). MiFID II will introduce new measures to increase transparency of research costs for clients of portfolio managers. Under these new measures, portfolio managers may only pay for research through their own funds or from a specific research payment account funded by its clients and subject to specific controls, including a research budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is also currently conducting a market study into asset management, which covers the issue of whether the level of fund management fees charged to consumers reflects a competitive market. We await the FCA’s assessment of competition in this sector. The FCA expect to publish an interim report in summer 2016 and a final report in early 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8185 ; HL8186 ; HL8188","2016-05-12T10:11:31.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517594/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517594/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Financial Services: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to legislate to ensure that all fees charged to pensioners by fund managers are made publicly available monthly, including transaction and research costs and all other costs that investors bear.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517595","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government is committed to the principle that people who have worked hard and saved should have access to appropriate and accessible investment options and understand the charges that they face. We appreciate the efforts that industry have made to fulfil this aim.</p><p> </p><p>Since last April, the Government has ensured that trustees of defined contribution pension schemes report charges levied on members in schemes used for auto enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>We are also engaging with international work on transparency, such as the legislation agreed at European Union level through the Packaged Retail and Insurance Based Investment Products (PRIIPs) and Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID). MiFID II will introduce new measures to increase transparency of research costs for clients of portfolio managers. Under these new measures, portfolio managers may only pay for research through their own funds or from a specific research payment account funded by its clients and subject to specific controls, including a research budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is also currently conducting a market study into asset management, which covers the issue of whether the level of fund management fees charged to consumers reflects a competitive market. We await the FCA’s assessment of competition in this sector. The FCA expect to publish an interim report in summer 2016 and a final report in early 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8185 ; HL8186 ; HL8187","2016-05-12T10:11:31.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517595/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517595/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-04","Financial Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they track the performance of the fund management industry; and if so, whether they have identified any examples where managers have been able to reduce costs and passed those reductions on to investors.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517596","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>When a fixed penalty notice is issued offenders have 28 days in which to pay the amount ordered. No enforcement action is taken during this period but if the offender fails to pay within this time the fixed penalty notice is increased by 50% and registered as a court fine. HM Courts and Tribunals Service can then take the same enforcement steps as for any court ordered fine.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-11T13:11:44.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517596/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517596/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-04","Cycling: Fixed Penalties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 3 May (HL7756), in what manner they ensure that cyclists pay fines imposed by fixed penalty notices.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL8189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517597","Department for Education","false","2016-05-12","<p>SATs, now called national curriculum tests, were first introduced in 1991. In determining primary assessment policy, the Department considers the impact of testing on all children as a matter of course, which includes drawing on evidence from this country’s past national tests.</p><p>As part of our Public Sector Equality Duty, we also consider the impact of Government policy on different groups of pupils, including – but not limited to – those with protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010. Vulnerable children, such as those from disadvantaged backgrounds who qualify for free school meals, looked-after children who attract pupil premium plus funding, or those with special educational needs.</p><p>The Government believes that rigorous and appropriate assessment is in all pupils’ interests. National curriculum tests help teachers to understand how pupils are doing in relation to national expectations and identify where additional support is needed. They also hold schools to account for how well they support their pupils, which the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development concludes is particularly important for the least advantaged. The tests should not put undue pressure on any pupil and we trust teachers to approach them in a proportionate manner. Schools are also required to provide continuous and appropriate support for the wellbeing and resilience of all pupils.</p><p>For this year, we have introduced updated tests to align with the new National Curriculum which was introduced in 2014. In developing the curriculum we have been mindful of the possible impact on equalities and based on a wide range of evidence we have conducted a full equalities impact assessment. This paper has been attached to this answer.</p><p>The new tests will assess pupils’ attainment against the National Curriculum. In developing these tests, the Department has considered carefully their impact upon all pupils and we will continue to do so as they are introduced in schools.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-05-12T11:29:53.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517597/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517597/answer","HL8190 Attachment.pdf","HL8190 Attachment.pdf","Reform_of_the_national_curriculum_England","Reform_of_the_national_curriculum_England","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517597/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-04","National Curriculum Tests","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the long-term impact of the introduction of SAT exams on vulnerable children.","false","Biography information for Baroness Afshar",,"Baroness Afshar","HL8190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517598","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-10","<p>Following Daesh's attack north of Mosul on 3 May, they were pushed back by Kurdish forces. The Kurds regained the lost territory with substantial Coalition air support, which included the use of RAF aircraft. UK assistance in Iraq is channelled, as appropriate, through the Government of Iraq or the Kurdish Regional Government rather than to any individual militia forces, and the UK has made no specific assessment of the objectives of the Nineveh Plain Forces.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-05-10T15:18:46.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517598/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517598/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-04","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of recent military attacks by ISIS on the Nineveh Plain Forces (NPF) at Telliskuf; what political and military assistance they are giving to the NPF; and what assessment they have made of the NPF’s objectives.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517599","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>We welcome all successes against Daesh. Ultimately, the best way of safeguarding minorities such as the Assyrians and the majority population is by defeating Daesh and establishing a lasting peace in both Syria and Iraq.</p><p>The Syriac Military Council has been a component part of the Kurdish People’s Protection Units (YPG)-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) since the SDF’s formation in late 2015. The SDF receives support from the Global Coalition in its efforts to combat Daesh in Northern Syria.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:29:03.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517599/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517599/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the campaign by the Syriac Military Council and its militia in recapturing territory, including Assyrian villages, from ISIS.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517600","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Syriac Military Council has been a component part of the Kurdish People's Protection Units (YPG)-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) since the SDF’s formation in late 2015. The SDF receives support from the International Coalition in its efforts to combat Daesh in Northern Syria.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:33:24.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517600/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517600/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the visit in January of British and French diplomats and American representatives to meet the Syriac coalition, what conclusions they have drawn about the military needs of that coalition.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517601","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>This Government condemns Daesh atrocities against Christians, other minorities, and the majority Muslim populations of Iraq and Syria. As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has said, the Government’s position remains that although there is a very strong case to answer, ultimately it should be a matter for judicial authorities.</p><p>We are supporting the gathering and preservation of evidence that could in future be used in a court to hold Daesh to account. And we continue to deliver our comprehensive strategy to defeat Daesh, and thereby stop them from preventing more atrocities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:34:02.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517601/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517601/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Middle East: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the legal advice given by the Attorney General in Northern Ireland that genocide is being committed against Christian and other minorities in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517602","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>The HS2 Sustainability Policy states that we will ‘source and make efficient use of sustainable materials.’ This includes the use of sustainable aggregates but is a purposely high-level statement intended to cover all types of sustainable materials. The detailed specifications for the sourcing and use of all materials, including aggregates, will be developed through the design process in line with the Sustainability Policy.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T11:19:21.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517602/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517602/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 4 May (HL7877), why they have not specified as part of their sustainability policy for HS2 the use of sustainable aggregates in the design of structures.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL8195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517603","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>Whilst the Farming Recovery Fund is not competitive, farmers wishing to apply to the Fund have to submit a formal application with evidence to support their need for a grant to contribute to the restoration of farmland badly affected by Storms Desmond or Eva. Payments are made to farmers once the work has been carried out and a claim has been submitted.</p><p> </p><p>The Rural Payments Agency (RPA) is responsible for determining the eligibility of Farming Recovery Fund applications, issuing grant funding agreements to eligible applicants, and receiving, processing and paying claims for costs incurred under those grant funding agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The RPA received 1,103 applications for a total value of grant of £11,429,194 by the closing dates for the scheme. As of 5 May 2016, 209 applications have been approved with a total value of £1,947,738. A further 20 applications, with a value of £265,440, have been either rejected as ineligible or withdrawn by the applicant.</p><p> </p><p>Of the projects approved, 29 have been completed and have submitted claims with a value of £202,268. 13 of these claims have been paid with a total value of £78,504.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-11T16:05:24.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517603/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517603/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","Floods: Agriculture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, of the 1,103 claims to the Flood Recovery Fund made by farmers in Cumbria, Northumberland, Lancashire, Yorkshire, County Durham and Greater Manchester, (1) who is responsible for approving those claims, (2) how many have been paid, and (3) what is the total value of those claims.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL8196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517604","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Farming Recovery Fund closed on 1 April in all areas except Greater Manchester, where it closed on 15 April. Of the total 1,103 applications received by 15 April, 515 were received in the week 28 March to 1 April and a further 18 were received by 15 April.</p><p> </p><p>The Rural Payments Agency (RPA) is taking measures to assess all the remaining applications received, including more staff resources and a review of the administrative checks required before approval. The RPA expects to process most applications by the end of May 2016.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-11T16:57:38.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517604/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517604/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","Floods: Agriculture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why processing claims to the Flood Recovery Fund have been delayed, and when they estimate that the processing of such claims will be completed.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL8197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517605","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK remains supportive of the Palestinian Authority’s (PA) efforts to strengthen its revenue generation. A transparent and effective tax system is an important part of this. It is also important that the tax system is implemented in a way that does not negatively impact the vital role which NGO’s play in responding to the needs of Palestinians in the Occupied Palestinian Territories is an importtant part of this.</p><p>DFID officials have raised concerns with the Ministry of Finance (MOF) about this, particularly the need for clarity on the implications of the tax system for NGOs, and how this could affect issues such as operations in Gaza and banking signatory authorities. The UK, along with other donors, UN OCHA and the NGO community, will continue to be in close contact with PA to clarify their approach.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-11T13:37:35.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517605/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517605/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-04","Gaza: Charities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on charities operating in Gaza of the freezing of financial transfers to them owing to the orders of the Palestinian Authority to Palestinian banks.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL8198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517606","Home Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The review of citizenship will look at how citizenship should be obtained in the future, both within the UK and the overseas territories. The overseas territories will be consulted as part of that review, and will have the opportunity to provide their views on a number of citizenship matters. The date for this consultation has not been finalised and details will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T13:05:32.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517606/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517606/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-04","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 25 April (HL7517), what is the timescale for the forthcoming review of British nationality law; and whether that review, and subsequent changes to citizenship legislation, will include the position of those of British Overseas Territories descent born before 1 July 2006 whose unmarried fathers automatically gained full British citizenship under the British Overseas Territories Act 2002.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL8199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517607","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>As is normal for large projects, the Cabinet Office’s Infrastructure and Projects Authority (IPA) is conducting assurance of the HS2 programme as it proceeds into its delivery phase. It is standard practice for this to include a small cross Government team, and not unusual for the Cabinet Secretary to take an interest on projects of this scale. ‎</p><p> </p><p>The IPAs role on the Government's Major Projects Portfolio is to provide expertise in infrastructure and the financing, delivery and assurance of major projects, to support more effective management and delivery across government. The assurance exercise is expected to feed into the next steps on delivery.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T11:18:12.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517607/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517607/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the terms of the review of HS2 being undertaken by Sir Jeremy Heywood; and when that review is expected to conclude.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL8200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517608","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>We have raised the case of Ilgar Mammadov on a number of occasions since his arrest in February 2013. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), and the Minister for Europe, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Aylesbury (Mr Lidington), raised it bilaterally with the Government of Azerbaijan during their visits to Baku in December 2013 and November 2014 respectively. The UK issued a press statement in March 2014, expressing concern about the length of the sentence and the conduct of the trial. In the Council of Europe the UK has repeatedly called for the Government of Azerbaijan to fully implement the European Court of Human Rights judgement and release Mr Mammadov.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:34:26.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517608/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517608/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Ilgar Mammadov","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Azerbaijan about the case of Ilga Mammadov.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL8201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517609","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>As I have explained in my previous replies to the noble Lord, the concept of ‘parity of esteem’ is expressed and defined in the 1998 Belfast Agreement in relation to people living in Northern Ireland. This Government sees parity of esteem as treating everybody in Northern Ireland fairly and with equal respect, just as it is committed to treating people fairly and with equal respect wherever they live in the United Kingdom.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","HL8203 ; HL8204","2016-05-12T10:23:07.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517609/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517609/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-05-04","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether parity of esteem as established in the Belfast Agreement 1998 applies to people who live in the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL8202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517610","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>As I have explained in my previous replies to the noble Lord, the concept of ‘parity of esteem’ is expressed and defined in the 1998 Belfast Agreement in relation to people living in Northern Ireland. This Government sees parity of esteem as treating everybody in Northern Ireland fairly and with equal respect, just as it is committed to treating people fairly and with equal respect wherever they live in the United Kingdom.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","HL8202 ; HL8204","2016-05-12T10:23:07.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517610/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517610/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-05-04","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether parity of esteem as established in the Belfast Agreement 1998 applies to (1) people temporarily residing in Northern Ireland, and if so for how long such people have to live there for parity of esteem to apply; and (2) people who live outside Northern Ireland but work in the province.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL8203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517611","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>As I have explained in my previous replies to the noble Lord, the concept of ‘parity of esteem’ is expressed and defined in the 1998 Belfast Agreement in relation to people living in Northern Ireland. This Government sees parity of esteem as treating everybody in Northern Ireland fairly and with equal respect, just as it is committed to treating people fairly and with equal respect wherever they live in the United Kingdom.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","HL8202 ; HL8203","2016-05-12T10:23:07.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517611/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517611/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-05-04","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the concept of parity of esteem in the Belfast Agreement 1998 means that people living in Northern Ireland are subject to more parity of esteem than anywhere else in the UK; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL8204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517612","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>This is an operational matter for Network Rail and London Underground.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T11:26:11.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517612/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517612/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-04","Railway Track","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many single line tracks there are on passenger lines within a 120 mile radius of all London rail stations; and what they are.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL8205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517613","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-12","<p>There has been no assessment of whether badger predation on hedgehogs is increasing or decreasing. Badgers have, however, been identified as one of a range of factors that could potentially have an impact on hedgehog populations.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-12T10:12:36.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517613/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517613/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-04","Hedgehogs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 25 April (HL7529), whether badger predation on hedgehogs is increasing or decreasing.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL8206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517614","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>While the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees already maintain an office in Rangoon, Burma, we have long called for the Burmese government to work with the UN over the opening of a full country office for the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights. This was a prominent recommendation of the Burma Resolution at the UN’s March Human Rights Council, which we co-sponsored. We will continue to encourage the new administration in Burma to follow through on that recommendation.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T14:49:47.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517614/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517614/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Burma: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the new government in Burma about the opening of a UNHCR office in that country.","false","Biography information for Baroness Nye",,"Baroness Nye","HL8207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>We did not hold discussions with the BBC World Service prior to their decision to move some Chinese Language Service posts to Hong Kong. Operational decisions of this nature are for the BBC to take independently of Government.</p><p>The BBC has since advised that the entire service is not moving to Hong Kong but that there will be a change in the number of staff based in Hong Kong and London to allow more first-hand reporting in the region.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:34:52.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517615/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","China: BBC World Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the BBC World Service regarding the proposal to move the Chinese Language Service to Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Baroness Falkner of Margravine",,"Baroness Falkner of Margravine","HL8208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517616","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>Russia’s use of disinformation and hybrid warfare is unacceptable. We are actively working with European and North Atlantic Treaty Organisation allies to protect and promote access to reliable information and bring balance and plurality to the Russian language media.</p><p>We are concerned by the harassment and detention of journalists in China. Freedom of expression is a priority for the UK and it should be the bedrock of a strong democracy. Working with the Chinese authorities and civil society to encourage greater freedom of expression in China remains a priority for us. In Hong Kong, we monitor freedom of the press closely, including in the Six Monthly Reports on Hong Kong, as this is one of the fundamental freedoms protected by the Joint Declaration and enshrined in the Basic Law</p><p>No assessment has been made regarding the operational decision to move some Chinese Language Service posts to Hong Kong. The BBC has advised that safety is always of paramount importance and BBC Chinese staff are already able to report from Hong Kong independently and without interference from authorities. The BBC believes this will continue in Hong Kong, which hosts regional headquarters and offices for more than a hundred leading international media organisations. The BBC faces challenges to press freedom all over the world every day and this move will not change its commitment to impartial journalism in any way.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:36:17.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517616/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517616/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Russia and China: Censorship","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their strategy to counter misinformation and censorship from Russia and China and what assessment they have made of how the relocation of the BBC Chinese Service to Hong Kong fits with that strategy, given the rise in Chinese intervention in freedoms in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Baroness Falkner of Margravine",,"Baroness Falkner of Margravine","HL8209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517617","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>We have not been informed by the BBC of any plans to move the Russian Service to Moscow. Operational decisions of this nature are for the BBC to take independently of Government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:36:33.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517617/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517617/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","Russia: BBC World Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have been informed of any plans by the BBC to move the Russian Service to Moscow.","false","Biography information for Baroness Falkner of Margravine",,"Baroness Falkner of Margravine","HL8210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517618","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>We have made no assessment regarding the operational decision to move some Chinese Language Service posts to Hong Kong. The BBC has advised that BBC Chinese Language staff are already able to report from Hong Kong independently and without interference from authorities. The BBC believes this will continue in Hong Kong which hosts regional headquarters and offices for more than a hundred leading international media organisations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:37:01.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517618/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517618/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-04","China: BBC World Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the editorial independence of the BBC Chinese Service of its potential relocation to Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Baroness Falkner of Margravine",,"Baroness Falkner of Margravine","HL8211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518349","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","In November, we announced a national ambition to halve the rates of stillbirths, neonatal and maternal deaths and brain injuries occurring during or soon after birth by 2030. Since then progress has included the launch of the ‘Spotlight on Maternity’ initiative and distribution of a £2.24 million capital fund for safety equipment.<p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T14:41:51.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518349/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518349/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Maternity Services: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress the Government has made on improving safety in maternity care.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","904960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518350","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","In considering the possible impact on patients of the increased charges for 2016/17 and for 2017/18, we concluded that the existing exemptions and Low Income Scheme will protect the most vulnerable, ensuring there should be no significant impact on an individual’s inclination to visit the dentist.","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-10T15:52:53.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518350/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518350/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Dental Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the proposed increase in charges for NHS dentistry on people's ability and inclination to visit a dentist regularly.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","904952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518351","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","We welcome the overall trend to longer life expectancy. Annual fluctuations in life expectancy do occur, but the overall trend remains positive. We are committed to helping people live longer, healthier lives. Tackling health inequalities amongst people of ages is embedded in policy right across the Department.<p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-10T15:51:51.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518351/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518351/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of recent trends in life expectancy.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","904951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518352","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","Hourly price caps are one part of a series of tough financial controls we introduced last year to help the National Health Service tackle overspending on agency staff. NHS Improvement consulted on the price caps before they were introduced and, with NHS England and the Care Quality Commission, has been monitoring their implementation on a weekly basis.","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T14:41:07.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518352/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518352/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department monitors implementation of price caps for agency staff.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","904958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518353","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","It is the responsibility of the Review Body on Doctors’ and Dentists’ Remuneration (DDRB) to make recommendations to government on the remuneration of doctors and dentists working in the National Health Service. We are also taking forward contract reform for consultants and junior doctors. The General Practitioner (GP) contract for 2016/17 will see an investment of £220 million for 2016/17 – part of this will provide a pay uplift of 1% for GPs.","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T15:54:11.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518353/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518353/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Doctors: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans the Government has for future changes in doctors' remuneration.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","904959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518354","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>A Full Business Case for the new inpatient ward at the Royal National Orthopaedic Hospital was submitted to NHS Improvement for review on 6 April 2016 and is due for consideration in June 2016. This remains a priority project for the Department and NHS Improvement.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-10T16:22:25.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518354/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518354/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","Royal National Orthopaedic Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on approving the business case for rebuilding the Royal National Orthopaedic Hospital.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","904956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518355","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","The Success Regime aims to improve the quality and sustainability of health and care services for local people.<p> </p>North, East and West Devon’s 'Case for Change' sets out the underlying challenges and opportunities. Change will be led by clinicians, in the best interests of communities. No specific proposals have been identified and the programme welcomes input from the people of North Devon. Hospital-based services will continue to be important across Devon, including in the North of the county.<p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T15:53:28.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518355/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518355/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","North Devon Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that the Success Regime review at North Devon District Hospital does not lead to a reduction in services provided at that hospital.","false","Biography information for Peter Heaton-Jones","North Devon","Peter Heaton-Jones","904955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518356","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","Final figures for 2015-16 are not yet available, but we know that the deficit will be bigger this year, and that there is significant pressure. This is why we are investing the additional £10 billion the National Health Service has said it needs to implement its own plan for the future, with £6 billion frontloaded by the end of next year.","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-10T14:38:46.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518356/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518356/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-04","NHS Trusts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of NHS trusts were in deficit at the end of 2015-16; and what the total size of that deficit was.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","904953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516951","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts for theft offences, and begging and sleeping out, in England and Wales, from 2012 to 2014 (latest available) can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts for selected offence categories, England and Wales, 2012 to 2014 <sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Offence category</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Theft offences</p></td><td><p>144,972</p></td><td><p>142,011</p></td><td><p>135,401</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Begging</p></td><td><p>1,229</p></td><td><p>2,097</p></td><td><p>2,219</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sleeping out</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(1) The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ref: PQ HL 8107</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on the value of the items involved in each individual theft offence is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The figures in the table can also be found in the Outcomes by Offence tables in the annual publication on the Government website.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-11T12:57:03.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516951/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516951/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-03","Crime: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prosecutions there have been in the past three years for (1) theft where the sum of money or the value of the goods alleged to have been taken is £10 or less, (2) begging, and (3) rough sleeping.","false","Biography information for Baroness Afshar",,"Baroness Afshar","HL8107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516952","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK has not made representations to Israel about this specific issue. We are in regular discussion with Israel, the Palestinian Authority and other development actors, specifically the UN and EU, about Gaza’s energy crisis. Improving Gaza’s provision of electricity will in turn improve Gaza’s water supply and wastewater treatment. We regularly call on both parties to work on solutions to increase the electricity supply, including press for the extension of the 161 power line and progress towards the conversion of the Gazan power station to gas.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-11T14:47:32.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516952/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516952/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-03","Gaza: Electricity Generation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Verma on 26 April (HL7737), what representations they have made to the government of Israel about why it rejected Turkey’s proposal of a floating power-generating ship to help solve the electricity crisis in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516953","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Government remains extremely concerned at the large increase in demolitions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories since the start of 2016, compared to the monthly average in 2015. We are not aware of any deaths which have resulted from demolitions. Our Embassy in Tel Aviv continues to regularly raise our concerns on demolitions with the Israeli authorities. As a result of these representations, the UK’s humanitarian and legal concerns on demolitions have been made clear.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-10T13:45:01.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516953/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516953/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 27 April (HL7738), what assessment they have made of the impact of their representations on the government of Israel with regard to house demolitions, in the light of the number of deaths and injuries caused during such incidents in the first three months of 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL8109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516954","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK fully supports the work of the UN Panel of Experts on Darfur. We are extremely concerned that last year’s report has not been published and have raised this issue with our UN Security Council partners.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:12:38.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516954/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516954/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Darfur","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what efforts they are making to press for the publication of the UN Security Council Sudan Panel of Experts’ most recent report, presented to the Sudan Sanctions Committee in December 2015, detailing the use of cluster munitions and gold smuggling in Darfur.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK consistently raises concerns about arbitrary detentions by the Government of Sudan’s security services, most recently as part of a joint démarche with the EU. The UK also took a lead role in helping to secure a new Commission on Human Rights at the UN Human Rights Council in March that will monitor and report on the human rights situation across South Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:13:20.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516955/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","South Sudan: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the calls by Amnesty International on 15 April that the South Sudanese government "must end arbitrary detentions by the intelligence agency", what steps they are taking to ensure that the South Sudanese National Security Service respects the human rights of those held in its custody.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL8111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516956","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>In recent years efficiency savings have been required right across HM Courts and Tribunals Service. Continuous improvement practices within compliance and enforcement have led to record totals of financial impositions collected each year for the last four years.</p><p>Following the decision to modernise the compliance and enforcement service through an in-house solution, HM Courts and Tribunals Service has been working to develop a new strategy which will lead to further investment in the service and further increased collections.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-11T12:57:28.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516956/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516956/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-03","Courts: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why spending on court fine collection is being cut, in the light of the value of fines that remain uncollected.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL8112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK is supporting the people of Eastern Sudan, including the Beja people, in a number of ways. The Department for International Development (DfID) spends £30million in Eastern Sudan to help improve vulnerable communities’ food security and nutrition, provide sustainable water supplies and improve sanitation. DfID also provides core funding to the UN High Commissioner for Refugees which supports host and refugee communities across Sudan to improve livelihoods and reduce the risk of human trafficking. The UK is also taking a lead role in the Khartoum Process, which prioritises tackling smuggling and trafficking across the Horn of Africa, including Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:14:27.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Sudan: Minority Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support the Beja people in Eastern Sudan, in particular to prevent kidnapping and people trafficking.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL8113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>While we welcome the positive steps the Government of Sudan has taken, including passing anti-trafficking legislation and acceding to the UN Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, we are concerned by reports of collusion between Sudanese border officials and traffickers. We continue to raise these concerns directly with the Government of Sudan and press for action.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-11T13:14:57.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Sudan: Human Trafficking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Human Rights Watch report of 2014<i> I Wanted to Lie Down and Die,</i> which stated that people trafficking was "facilitated by collusion between traffickers and Sudanese and Egyptian police", what assessment they have made of any current links between the government of Sudan and people traffickers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL8114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516959","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK continues to fund international non-governmental organisations (INGOs) and UN agencies to deliver programmes which target the most vulnerable Sudanese citizens, and ensure that those in need of humanitarian assistance are not left unsupported as a result of expulsion decisions. We meet regularly with the Sudan INGO Steering Committee to discuss issues including humanitarian access, and support them in advocating for access when requested to do so. In addition, DFID is funding £30m of programmes over 3 years in Eastern Sudan to help improve vulnerable communities’ food security and nutrition, provide sustainable water supplies and improve sanitation. DFID also provides core funding to the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) which supports host and refugee communities across Sudan to improve livelihoods.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-11T13:39:12.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516959/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516959/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-03","Sudan: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that humanitarian charities such as Save the Children and Médecins Sans Frontières are able to give assistance to people in Eastern Sudan, following their expulsion by the government of Sudan in June 2012.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL8115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516960","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK uses the EU PEGASE mechanism to earmark funds to payment of vetted PA civil servants and pensioners. The list of PEGASE Direct Financial Support eligible beneficiaries is determined each month by Deloitte auditors on the basis of the EU eligibility criteria. The list of approved recipients is subject to a vetting process that includes screening against international (including Israeli) ad hoc sanctions lists.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-11T15:43:44.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516960/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516960/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-03","Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Verma on 25 April (HL7413), how the pre-approved EU list of named civil servants is approved, and by whom; and how that process is subject to independent auditing, and by whom.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL8116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516961","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-12","<p>DFID is currently reviewing all its programmes following the publication of the updated Official Development Assistance strategy last year. DFID provides financial support to the Palestinian Authority (PA) to help deliver peace and support progress towards a two state solution. DFID funding helps build Palestinian institutions and promotes economic growth so that any future Palestinian state will be a prosperous and effective partner for peace. UK funding to the PA is for vetted civil servants only.</p><p>The PA has reaffirmed that prisoner payments are administered by the Palestinian Liberation Organisation. We continue to lobby that the payments to prisoner’s families are more transparent and needs-based.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-05-12T10:17:18.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516961/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516961/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-03","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have given any consideration to suspending aid to the Palestinian Authority in the light of its decision to transfer over £85 million a year to the Palestine Liberation Organisation for the purpose of paying salaries to convicted terrorists imprisoned in Israel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL8117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516962","Department for Education","false","2016-05-10","<p>The current dual system, where maintained schools and academies (including free schools) have different requirements on a number of key areas including funding, financial compliance, performance oversight, parental complaints and how they are required to adhere to legislation, does not provide consistent expectations on professionals or clarity and assurance for pupils and parents.</p><p>This government believes a single system with all schools as academies, which affords greater autonomy to professionals and is governed by a single legal framework along with clear and robust accountability, will provide a level playing field for all and the conditions for future success. It will give clarity on roles and responsibilities and secure efficiency. Running a dual system diverts resources, time and focus away from the classroom.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-05-10T14:51:31.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516962/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516962/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Schools: Costs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the costs of running different education systems in respect of local education authority maintained schools, academies, and free schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516963","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>Taking the Spending Review and the Budget together, we have set aside the funding to support a high quality school system where all schools are academies.</p><p>Through the Budget and the Department for Education’s settlement in the Spending Review there are sufficient resources available to take advantage of the opportunities presented by all schools becoming academies. The Government has allocated £300 million that will be available to support schools to convert and, in particular, support sponsors to turn around failing schools. A further £300 million will be available to support strong and effective multi-academy trusts to grow and improve.</p><p>The Department will be issuing further detail on how funding will support the conversion of all schools to academy status in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-05-11T11:37:47.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516963/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516963/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Academies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what the costs will be of the proposed conversion of all non-academies to academy schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516964","Department for Education","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department published a supplementary analysis to the academies annual report in June 2013 which included analysis of the 2012 results for sponsored secondary academies compared to similar local authority maintained schools. The paper has been attached to this answer.</p><p>Our success in meeting our commitment to tackle failing schools by bringing in academy sponsors means that there is no longer a large enough pool of maintained secondary schools to allow a robust approach to identifying similar schools against which we can assess academy performance, such as the matching methodology used in our June 2013 analysis. A matching approach has been used in other analysis of primary schools such as that published in May 2016 by SchoolDash to conclude that sponsored academies “become noticeably better in a relatively short time following academy conversion.”</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-05-12T11:30:35.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516964/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516964/answer","HL8120 attachment.pdf","HL8120 attachment.pdf","Attainment_by_pupils_in_academies_2012","Attainment_by_pupils_in_academies_2012","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516964/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","GCSE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what analysis they have carried out of the performance of sponsored academy schools compared to similar local authority maintained schools based on GCSE results in (1) 2013, (2) 2014, and (3) 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516965","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>All follow up appointments (also known as planned, surveillance or recall appointments) should take place when clinically appropriate. It is for clinicians to make decisions on when they see patients, in line with their clinical priority, and patients should not experience undue delay at any stage of their referral, diagnosis or treatment. Moreover, the appropriate interval for follow up appointments will vary between different services or specialties, and between individual patients, depending on the severity of their condition.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure that patients are seen at the appropriate time, NHS England guidance is clear that when patients on planned lists are clinically ready for their care to commence and reach the date for their planned appointment, they should either receive that appointment or be transferred to an active waiting list. At that point, a waiting time clock will be started and their wait reported in the relevant statistical return, so that patients are not waiting on ‘hidden’ lists.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, the Care Quality Commission (CQC) also assesses providers against the new fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fail. One of these standards requires that care and treatment must be appropriate and reflect service users’ needs and preferences. Another requires that care and treatment must be provided in a safe way. The CQC will require a provider to improve where it is not meeting these standards.</p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the clinical risks to patients of follow-up appointments being scheduled beyond clinically recommended times, as the risks will also vary between services, specialties and patients. It is for clinicians to make these judgements.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on delays to review outpatient appointments is not collected centrally.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL8122 ; HL8123","2016-05-11T15:59:51.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516965/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516965/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Out-patients: Waiting Lists","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what mechanisms are in place to safeguard patients from delays to return hospital appointments beyond the clinically recommended time.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8121"
