"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517119","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) published its latest tax gap estimates on 22 October 2015 in Measuring tax gaps 2015 edition, which is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470540/HMRC-measuring-tax-gaps-2015-1.pdf</p><p> </p><p>Tables 1.2 and 1.4 of the Measuring tax gaps 2015 edition show different information. Table 1.2 looks specifically at the large business Corporation Tax gap as a percentage of theoretical liabilities for large business Corporation Tax, and Table 1.4 expresses the tax gap for all large businesses taxes (including VAT and income taxes) as a percentage of all theoretical liabilities for all HMRC customer groups. Trends in tax gaps for specific taxes and customer groups are different.</p><p> </p><p>Measuring Tax Gaps does not include full detailed segmentation, such as the requested large business customer group by type of tax, as a number of segments at this level are not sufficiently robust for publication. Table 6.9 on page 53 provides information on the estimated tax gap for large employers.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T13:21:33.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517119/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517119/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to tables 1.2 and 1.4 of HM Revenue and Customs' document, Measuring tax gaps, published in October 2013, what assessment HM Revenue and Customs has made of the reasons for which the corporation tax gap for large businesses has narrowed as a percentage while the overall percentage tax gap for large businesses has remained the same since 2009-10; and if he will estimate the large business tax gap for each tax in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517120","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs published its latest tax gap estimates on 22 October 2015 in Measuring tax gaps 2015 edition. This is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470540/HMRC-measuring-tax-gaps-2015-1.pdf</p><p> </p><p>The tax gap by behaviour is set out in Figure 1.6 (page 11) and Table 1.5 (page 19). As behaviour estimates are made using management assumptions and judgement, they should be used as a broad indication.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T13:23:18.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517120/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517120/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Black Economy and Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to table 1.5 of HM Revenue and Customs' document, Measuring tax gaps, published in October 2013, how much revenue was lost as a result of the tax gap in (a) tax evasion and (b) the hidden economy in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517121","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK’s first Tax Inspectors Without Borders Agreement was signed in December 2015. A partnership agreement was signed with Lesotho committing the UK to a two and a half year programme of assistance. Two HMRC tax experts will be providing support under this Agreement.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T10:07:18.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517121/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517121/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2016 to Questions 33571 and 33572, how many tax auditors HM Revenue and Customs provided to Tax Inspectors Without Borders in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517122","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK expects to receive information from the following jurisdictions under the automatic exchange of information agreements it has, or will soon have, in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Albania</p></td><td><p>Colombia</p></td><td><p>Hong Kong</p></td><td><p>Marshall Islands</p></td><td><p>Seychelles</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Andorra</p></td><td><p>Cook Islands</p></td><td><p>Hungary</p></td><td><p>Mauritius</p></td><td><p>Singapore</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Anguilla</p></td><td><p>Costa Rica</p></td><td><p>Iceland</p></td><td><p>Mexico</p></td><td><p>Sint Maarten</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Antigua &amp; Barbuda</p></td><td><p>Croatia</p></td><td><p>India</p></td><td><p>Monaco</p></td><td><p>Slovak Republic</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Argentina</p></td><td><p>Curacao</p></td><td><p>Indonesia</p></td><td><p>Montserrat</p></td><td><p>Slovenia</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aruba</p></td><td><p>Cyprus</p></td><td><p>Ireland</p></td><td><p>Netherlands</p></td><td><p>South Africa</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Austria</p></td><td><p>Czech Republic</p></td><td><p>Isle of Man</p></td><td><p>New Zealand</p></td><td><p>Spain</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bahamas</p></td><td><p>Denmark</p></td><td><p>Israel</p></td><td><p>Niue</p></td><td><p>Sweden</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Barbados</p></td><td><p>Dominica</p></td><td><p>Italy</p></td><td><p>Norway</p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Belgium</p></td><td><p>Estonia</p></td><td><p>Japan</p></td><td><p>Poland</p></td><td><p>Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Belize</p></td><td><p>Faroe Islands</p></td><td><p>Jersey</p></td><td><p>Portugal</p></td><td><p>Turkey</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bermuda</p></td><td><p>Finland</p></td><td><p>Korea</p></td><td><p>Qatar</p></td><td><p>Turks &amp; Caicos Islands</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brazil</p></td><td><p>France</p></td><td><p>Kuwait</p></td><td><p>Romania</p></td><td><p>United Arab Emirates</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>British Virgin Islands</p></td><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>Latvia</p></td><td><p>Russian Federation</p></td><td><p>Uruguay</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brunei Darassulam</p></td><td><p>Ghana</p></td><td><p>Liechtenstein</p></td><td><p>St Kitts &amp; Nevis</p></td><td><p>United States*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bulgaria</p></td><td><p>Gibraltar</p></td><td><p>Lithuania</p></td><td><p>St Lucia</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>Greece</p></td><td><p>Luxembourg</p></td><td><p>St Vincent &amp; the Grenadines</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cayman Islands</p></td><td><p>Greenland</p></td><td><p>Macao</p></td><td><p>Samoa</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chile</p></td><td><p>Grenada</p></td><td><p>Malaysia</p></td><td><p>San Marino</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>China</p></td><td><p>Guernsey</p></td><td><p>Malta</p></td><td><p>Saudi Arabia</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>*The United States has committed to move to full reciprocation of data exchange under the Inter-Governmental Agreement of 12 September 2012. The domestic legislation required in the US for this to happen has not yet been put in place and we have no indication of when this will happen. Until then the UK will continue to receive limited information collected by the Internal Revenue Service under existing regulations –this pertains to interest bearing financial accounts, but not trusts.</p><p> </p><p>The use of the information received is governed by the international agreements under which it is exchanged. As these are international agreements concerned with taxation matters, the information is restricted in its use to the administration, assessment, and collection of taxes covered by the agreement in question for each jurisdiction. As these are functions of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), only HMRC can use the information without further recourse to the sending jurisdiction and the primary use must be the functions of HMRC. Sharing the information found to be relevant to other Government Agencies with those other Agencies is only permitted where the international agreement allows it, and the sending jurisdiction gives express permission that it can be so shared by HMRC. HMRC will always seek to share the information where relevant and possible, and it is our policy to ensure that new agreements and amendments to existing agreements allow such sharing.</p><p> </p><p>The UK expects that most of the automatic exchange agreements with the jurisdictions listed above will be reciprocal. However, not all jurisdictions require information from the UK and in those cases the UK will receive information but send nothing the other way.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T13:10:09.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517122/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517122/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Tax Havens","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 32849, which 90 countries will provide automatic offshore account and trust data to the UK; which responsible authorities in the UK will be able to access that data; and whether the 90 countries referred to will also be able to access automatic offshore account and trust data held by the UK.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517123","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>Until 31 March 2014, HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Large Business Service dealt with the tax affairs of around 800 of the largest businesses in the UK. From 1 April 2014 HMRC’s Large Business directorate deals with the tax affairs of around 2,000 large businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not centrally hold large business receipts data for every tax heading, the information for every tax heading could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. The number of large businesses and the tax receipts data held centrally for large businesses is:</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s Large Business directorate:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Number of Businesses</p></td><td><p>Corporation Tax</p></td><td><p>Income Tax, National Insurance</p></td><td><p>VAT</p></td><td><p>Hydrocarbon Oils</p></td><td><p>Alcohol &amp; Tobacco</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2,145</p></td><td><p>£20bn</p></td><td><p>£85bn</p></td><td><p>£52bn</p></td><td><p>£27bn</p></td><td><p>£14bn</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>HMRC’s Large Business Service:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Number of Businesses</p></td><td><p>Corporation Tax</p></td><td><p>Income Tax, National Insurance</p></td><td><p>VAT</p></td><td><p>Hydrocarbon Oils</p></td><td><p>Alcohol &amp; Tobacco</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>818</p></td><td><p>£17bn</p></td><td><p>£68bn</p></td><td><p>£41bn</p></td><td><p>£26bn</p></td><td><p>£13bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>803</p></td><td><p>£17bn</p></td><td><p>£64bn</p></td><td><p>£41bn</p></td><td><p>£26bn</p></td><td><p>£13bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>783</p></td><td><p>£21bn</p></td><td><p>£65bn</p></td><td><p>£40bn</p></td><td><p>£26bn</p></td><td><p>£13bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>778</p></td><td><p>£21bn</p></td><td><p>£62bn</p></td><td><p>£34bn</p></td><td><p>£26bn</p></td><td><p>£10bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>760</p></td><td><p>£20bn</p></td><td><p>£58bn</p></td><td><p>£30bn</p></td><td><p>£24bn</p></td><td><p>£11bn</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The number of full-time equivalent staff on the payrolls of businesses is not required for tax purposes and HMRC does not hold it.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T13:33:12.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517123/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517123/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many large businesses were recorded on HM Revenue and Customs' database in each year since 2009-10; how many full-time equivalent staff were on the payrolls of such businesses; and how much in each business tax was paid by such businesses in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517124","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>Information on the key data and assumptions underpinning the costing of the soft drinks industry levy announced at Budget 2016 is available at page 12 in the Budget 2016 policy costings document available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-11T10:23:05.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517124/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517124/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether industry analysts data was consulted in preparing the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","36358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517125","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>This information is not available. This is because HMRC do not ask for a country-by-country breakdown on the taxpayer’s return.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-11T10:40:52.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517125/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517125/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Gaming Machines: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has accrued to the public purse from use of fixed-odds betting terminals in (a) Northern Ireland, (b) Wales, (c) Scotland and (d) England in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","36381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517126","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>Regulation of Fixed Odds betting Terminals is devolved and in Northern Ireland it is the responsibility of the Northern Ireland Department for Communities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-11T10:20:59.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517126/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517126/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-03","Gaming Machines: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of fixed-odds betting terminals operating in Northern Ireland in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","36382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517127","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Department’s annual Green Belt statistics monitor the amount of land designated as Green Belt in England. The latest figures for 2014-15 show that 1,900 hectares of land in Poole Unitary Authority was designated as Green Belt. This is 29% of the land area of Poole Unitary Authority.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-09T15:46:10.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517127/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517127/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-03","Green Belt: Poole","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 19682, how much land in Poole Unitary Authority in hectares is designated as Green Belt.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","36345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517128","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-09","<p>A consultation on specific changes to the Framework, aimed at increasing housing supply in sustainable locations, closed on 22 February. We are analysing the responses and will publish the results of the consultation when we issue the revised Framework.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-09T15:46:39.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517128/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517128/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-03","Planning: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish the results of the consultation on proposed changes to the National Planning Policy Framework which concluded on 22 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","36321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517129","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Syon Lane site was acquired by the Department for Communities and Local Government on behalf of the Education Funding Agency (EFA) as a permanent site for Nishkam School West London. When full, the school will provide 1,400 places for local children.</p><p> </p><p>Where possible, sites for new free schools are secured with exchange subject to planning approval. The decision to proceed with the purchase was taken following confirmation from Hounslow Local Planning Authority that the proposal to develop a school on the site would be consistent with local planning policies, so an argument could be made for such a development.</p><p> </p><p>The land valuation undertaken to inform the purchase took account of its designation as Metropolitan Open Land and an estimation of the value of the land should its planning status change to permit the construction of a school building.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-09T17:10:59.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517129/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517129/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517129/answer/previousversion/59795","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Free Schools: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons her Department acquired the land for the new Nishkam School site in West London before planning permission for that school was granted; and whether the valuation of that land was based on an assumption that planning permission would be granted.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","36285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517130","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-09","<p>239 of 338 local planning authorities (71%) have an adopted Local Plan and 287 (85%) have published a Local Plan. Approximately 67% of England’s land area is covered by adopted Local Plans and 87% covered by published plans.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-09T15:42:21.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517130/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517130/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-03","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2015 to Question 9722, what proportion of land is now covered by a local plan.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","36338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517131","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given by my Rt Hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General today. UIN: 36288</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-05-11T14:59:02.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517131/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517131/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-03","Communities and Local Government: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517132","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Coastal Communities Fund awards grants to projects through a competitive bid-led process and is not allocated directly to specific places or Coastal Community Teams (CCTs). Funds are awarded to projects that best meet the programme's aims to promote sustainable growth and jobs.</p><p>The Fund's next bidding round (Round 4) for projects in England starting in 2017-18 is expected to open for new applications in early Summer 2016. Full details of how to apply will be available on the Big Lottery Fund’s web site: <a href="https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/ccf" target="_blank">https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/ccf</a></p><p>The Economic Plan submitted by Jaywick's CCT earlier this year will provide an important context for considering bids to the Fund from public, private and voluntary/community sector bodies in the area.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-05-09T15:40:57.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517132/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517132/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-03","Coastal Communities Fund: Jaywick","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding from the Coastal Communities Fund will be allocated to the Jaywick Coastal Community Team between 2017 and 2021.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517133","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer the my hon. Friend to the answer given by my Rt Hon. Friend, the Minister for the Cabinet Office today to UIN 36288.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-11T14:15:32.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517133/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517133/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-03","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517134","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-10","<p>In April 2015 the previous Government introduced regulations which require authorisation of stakes over £50 on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals through a “verified account” or staff interaction. The Government published its evaluation of the £50 regulations on 21 January. The evaluation paper can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-gaming-machine-circumstances-of-useamendment-regulations-2015.</p><p> </p><p>We will now consider the findings of the evaluation before deciding if there is a need for further action.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-05-10T12:56:15.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517134/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517134/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-03","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the triennial review of (a) stake and (b) prize limits in fixed-odds betting terminals has not yet been published; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","36380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517135","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given today by my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office to Question 36288.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-05-11T15:15:51.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517135/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517135/answer","20160511_36288_EU_Law.docx","20160511_36288_EU_Law.docx","36288 - QnA extract on EU Law","36288 - QnA extract on EU Law","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517135/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-03","Ministry of Defence: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517136","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-09","<p>We are strongly committed to gliding and flying in the Air Cadet Organisation. Our immediate priority is to get cadets back flying again, after a gap of about two years. That will start again this year, and should be fully delivered by 2018.</p><p>The cadets of West Sussex glide with 615 Volunteer Gliding Squadron (VGS) at RAF Kenley and this will continue. This VGS is being expanded as a regional hub, with a project under way to deliver a new operations and accommodation block.</p><p>They will also continue to undertake Tutor Air Experience Flights with 6 Air Experience Flight based at RAF Benson.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-05-09T15:20:00.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517136/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517136/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-03","Air Force: Cadets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department provides to air cadet units in West Sussex to participate in (a) gliding and (b) other flying activities.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","36337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517137","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>The amount spent on the Troops to Teachers scheme by financial year is listed below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount spent on the Troops to Teacher scheme</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£1.7m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£976,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-11T16:06:57.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517137/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517137/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of the Troops to Teachers scheme in each year since that scheme began; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517138","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Secretary of State, Ministers and officials at the Department regularly receive many representations from head teachers about schools converting to academies. All of the Department’s responses make clear that the conversion of schools to academies is part of the Government’s commitment to achieve educational excellence everywhere.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-11T16:07:56.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517138/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517138/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many representations she has received from headteachers on academisation in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517139","Department for Education","false","2016-05-10","<p>Total pupil premium allocations for schools in Coventry local authority for each year are:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium Allocations (£millions)</strong></p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coventry local authority (including academies)</p></td><td><p>5.157</p></td><td><p>9.299</p></td><td><p>14.383</p></td><td><p>18.858</p></td><td><p>18.634</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-05-10T16:03:56.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517139/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517139/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Pupil Premium: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the total amount paid in pupil premium funding to schools in Coventry in each year since the beginning of such funding; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517140","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>As set out in our recent White Paper, Educational Excellence Everywhere, we plan to introduce ‘Centres of Excellence’ in Initial Teacher Training which will receive multi-year allocations. We are currently engaging the sector and working to establish the criteria for determining which providers will be designated as a ‘Centre of Excellence’. At this stage, no firm decisions have been taken.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","36324 ; 36325","2016-05-09T14:04:36.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517140/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517140/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 2.30 of her Department's white paper,  Educational Excellence Everywhere, published in March 2016, what evidence her Department is taking into account to decide which (a) metrics and (b) other factors will be used to decide which providers are awarded multi-year allocations of initial teacher training places.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517141","Department for Education","true","2016-05-12","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">In order to complete initial teacher training successfully, all trainees must meet the Teachers’ Standards in full. The standards emphasise the importance of the basics of good teaching, such as strong subject knowledge and effective behaviour management. Following the review teacher training by Sir Andrew Carter, we have a commissioned an expert group to develop a new framework of content for training, based closely on the Teachers’ Standards and reiterating the requirement to place a clear focus on essentials such as the effective development of subject knowledge and being able to identify and respond to special educational needs. The group will be making its recommendations to Ministers shortly.</ins></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-12T12:15:13.733Z","2016-05-13T09:53:43.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517141/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517141/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517141/answer/previousversion/60912","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the relationship between the degree classifications of trainee teachers with their later performance in a teaching career.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517142","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>As set out in our recent White Paper, Educational Excellence Everywhere, we plan to introduce ‘Centres of Excellence’ in Initial Teacher Training which will receive multi-year allocations. We are currently engaging the sector and working to establish the criteria for determining which providers will be designated as a ‘Centre of Excellence’. At this stage, no firm decisions have been taken.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","36308 ; 36325","2016-05-09T14:04:36.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517142/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517142/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 2.28 of her Department's white paper Educational Excellence Everywhere, published in March 2016, what factors will be taken into account in assessing which graduates are well-qualified for a teaching career for the purposes of the allocation of initial teacher training places to university providers.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517143","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>As set out in our recent White Paper, Educational Excellence Everywhere, we plan to introduce ‘Centres of Excellence’ in Initial Teacher Training which will receive multi-year allocations. We are currently engaging the sector and working to establish the criteria for determining which providers will be designated as a ‘Centre of Excellence’. At this stage, no firm decisions have been taken.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","36308 ; 36324","2016-05-09T14:04:36.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517143/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517143/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the statistical or other criteria are which her Department plans to apply in assessing which providers are to be given a multi-year allocation of initial teacher training places.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517144","Department for Education","true","2016-05-12","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">In order to complete initial teacher training successfully, all trainees must meet the Teachers’ Standards in full. The standards emphasise the importance of the basics of good teaching, such as strong subject knowledge and effective behaviour management. Following the review teacher training by Sir Andrew Carter, we have a commissioned an expert group to develop a new framework of content for training, based closely on the Teachers’ Standards and reiterating the requirement to place a clear focus on essentials such as the effective development of subject knowledge and being able to identify and respond to special educational needs. The group will be making its recommendations to Ministers shortly.</ins></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-12T12:15:36.38Z","2016-05-13T09:53:33.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517144/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517144/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517144/answer/previousversion/60913","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on evidence suggesting a link between the A-level results of trainee teachers and their later performance when in a teaching career.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517145","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>Academy trusts have the freedom to make decisions which reflect the local circumstances of their school. We expect these decisions to be made in a fair and transparent way.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-09T17:10:25.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517145/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517145/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517145/answer/previousversion/59794","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what provision academy trusts have to charge teachers for car parking services on school grounds; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517146","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer given by my Rt Hon Friend, the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in PQ 36288 on 11 May 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-11T16:36:49.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517146/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517146/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Department for Education: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517147","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>Independent schools have to meet the standards set in regulations. If segregation results in disadvantage for pupils of one gender, either directly or through inappropriate modelling of gender roles through staff segregation visible to pupils, then it is likely that the standards have not been met and regulatory action by this Department will follow. If there is a possibility that staff segregation disadvantages staff of one gender and there may be a direct breach of the Equality Act 2010, we will not hesitate to make a referral to the Equality and Human Rights Commission.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-11T16:27:35.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517147/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517147/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Faith Schools: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to reduce the incidence of gender segregation in some Muslim independent schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","36350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517148","Department for Education","false","2016-05-10","<p>Career Colleges will have their own branding and identity and are independent of Government policy, so it is not for Government to promote them directly. However, we do support any organisation which is focused on providing high quality technical education to young people.</p><p>In particular, we hope Career Colleges can benefit from the protection of funding and the range of flexibilities in the system. This includes protecting the 16-19 base rate, substantial investment in apprenticeships and study programmes, which provide an opportunity to tailor provision around the needs and aspirations of each young person.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-10T13:35:04.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517148/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517148/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Further Education: Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she has taken to promote career colleges; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","36242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517149","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Children and Families Act 2014 requires local authorities to develop and publish a Local Offer setting out the support they expect to be available for children and young people with special educational needs or disabilities in their local area. The Local Offer must include information about leisure activities which may include information about play opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>The Ofsted and Care Quality Commission (CQC) inspections will consider how effectively the local area identifies, meets the needs of and improves the outcomes of the wide range of different groups<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> of children and young people who have special educational needs or disabilities as defined in the Act and described in the Code of Practice.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted and CQC will draw on a range of sources, including the local offer, to identify key lines of enquiry and to support assessment of the effectiveness of the local area.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted and CQC will publish an inspection report that will outline the evidence that inspectors reviewed and provide a summary of key findings including the local area’s strengths and areas requiring further development.</p><p> </p><p>The inspection framework and handbook are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-area-send-inspection-framework" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-area-send-inspection-framework</a></p><p> </p><p>[1] These groups of children and young people are detailed in Part 2 of the ‘Handbook for the inspection of local areas’ effectiveness in identifying and meeting the needs of children and young people who have special educational needs and/or disabilities’.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-09T14:52:13.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517149/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517149/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to ensure that proposed Ofsted local area inspections include a requirement that Local Offers should contain clear information about local play opportunities and entitlements.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517150","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Education and Skills Act 2008 requires young people to participate in education or training until they are 18. Young people can participate through full-time education, work combined with part-time education or training, or by undertaking an apprenticeship or traineeship.</p><p> </p><p>The 16 and 17 year olds joining the armed forces are under a contract of employment but they are not exempt from their duty to participate. Most of these young people meet their duty to participate by undertaking an apprenticeship.</p><p> </p><p>We have agreed with the Ministry of Defence that serving in the armed forces is a valid and valuable career route which provides relevant training for young people.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are embedded across initial training in the armed forces, with over 95% of all young recruits (no matter what their age or prior qualifications) enrolling in an apprenticeship each year.</p><p> </p><p>All apprenticeships require a minimum of 280 Guided Learning Hours (GLHs) within a 12 month period. The same GLH requirement applies to the small number of young people in the armed forces who are not on an apprenticeship.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","36266","2016-05-09T16:02:51.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517150/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517150/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Armed Forces: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations her Department received on exempting the armed forces from providing recruits under the age of 18 with the minimum standards required under the Education and Skills Act 2008; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517151","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>The proportion of 16 and 17 year olds in full-time education in England was 70.3% at the end of 2005 and 82.2% at the end of 2014 (provisional figures). These figures are published in Table A7 of the ‘Additional tables – rates’ in the Statistical First Release (SFR) ‘Participation in education, training and employment’ and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-neet" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-neet</a></p><p> </p><p>Figures for end 2015 are not yet available but will be published on 30<sup>th</sup> June 2016 as part of the above series.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-09T14:03:58.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517151/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517151/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","School Leaving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of 16 and 17 year olds participated in full-time education in England in (a) 2005 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517152","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Education and Skills Act 2008 requires young people to participate in education or training until they are 18. Young people can participate through full-time education, work combined with part-time education or training, or by undertaking an apprenticeship or traineeship.</p><p> </p><p>The 16 and 17 year olds joining the armed forces are under a contract of employment but they are not exempt from their duty to participate. Most of these young people meet their duty to participate by undertaking an apprenticeship.</p><p> </p><p>We have agreed with the Ministry of Defence that serving in the armed forces is a valid and valuable career route which provides relevant training for young people.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are embedded across initial training in the armed forces, with over 95% of all young recruits (no matter what their age or prior qualifications) enrolling in an apprenticeship each year.</p><p> </p><p>All apprenticeships require a minimum of 280 Guided Learning Hours (GLHs) within a 12 month period. The same GLH requirement applies to the small number of young people in the armed forces who are not on an apprenticeship.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","36264","2016-05-09T16:02:51.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517152/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517152/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Armed Forces: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department requires the armed forces to provide entrants aged under 18 with 280 guided learning hours per year towards accredited qualifications.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517153","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>For the 2016/17 Initial Teacher Training (ITT) recruitment round, the Department operated a system of recruitment controls and not allocations. We continue to monitor daily the recruitment at a regional level and have the power to enact regional controls if we see a large disparity in recruitment for a region. A guide to the 2016/17 ITT recruitment round methodology can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468099/ITT_recruitment_control_guidance_2016-17_v1.1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468099/ITT_recruitment_control_guidance_2016-17_v1.1.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>We are currently engaging the sector and working to establish the criteria for determining which providers will be designated as a ‘Centre of Excellence’ and receive multi-year allocations, but at this stage no firm decisions have been taken.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-09T14:02:54.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517153/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517153/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-03","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the level of regional variation in the proportion of initial teacher training places allocated to providers with an outstanding Ofsted rating in the last 12 months for which figures are available; and whether her Department plans to take such variation into account when assessing which providers will be given a multi-year allocation of initial teacher training places.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","36369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517154","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-06","<p>By the end of March 2016, there were</p><ul><li><p>722,559 households with solar PV benefitting from feed-in-tariff (FIT) payments.</p></li><li><p>45,789 households with installations benefitting from renewable heat incentive (RHI) payments</p></li></ul><p>The number of households in receipt of both FIT and RHI payments is not available.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source data:</em></p><p><em>FIT: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics</a></em></p><p><em>RHI: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-deployment-data-march-2016-q1-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-deployment-data-march-2016-q1-2016</a> (table 2.10)</em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-06T13:29:15.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517154/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517154/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-03","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households are in receipt of (a) feed-in tariff payments from solar PV installations, (b) domestic renewal heat incentive payments and (c) both such payments.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","36379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517155","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given to her by my rt. hon. Friend the Minister of State for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General today to Question 36288:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-05-03/36288/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-05-03/36288/</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-05-11T12:27:50.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517155/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517155/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much her Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517156","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Bonfield Review is due to report back its findings later this year.</p><p>We are confident that the Bonfield Review will provide a real opportunity to put energy efficiency and renewable energy on a more consumer-focussed and sustainable long-term path for the future.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-05T12:47:43.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517156/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517156/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-03","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she plans to publish the recommendations of the Bonfield Review of consumer advice, protection, standards and enforcement for energy efficiency and renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","36320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517157","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given by the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General, the Rt. Hon Matthew Hancock, on 11 May 2016, to PQ UIN 36288.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-11T12:46:56.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517157/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517157/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-03","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much her Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517158","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-09","<p>Significant or technically complex applications for authorisation are considered by the UK Expert Committee on Pesticides. Their agendas and minutes are published and provide public information about the expert assessment, including details of the applications considered.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-09T15:24:28.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517158/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517158/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-03","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will direct the Health and Safety Executive to increase transparency by publishing details of applications for emergency authorisation of neonicotinoid pesticides before a decision is taken on such applications.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","36279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517159","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 22 June 2015, PQ UIN 2954.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-09T10:42:55.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517159/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517159/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-03","Meat: Ritual Slaughter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to bring forward legislative proposals for the labelling of ritually slaughtered meat products.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","36248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517161","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Government issued emergency authorisations in 2015 for the limited and controlled use of neonicotinoid seed treatments on oilseed rape. One of the conditions attached to these authorisations was that the authorisation holder should use the authorised area to generate data on both treated and untreated crops. This should include impact on adult and larval numbers, crop establishment/damage and effects on crop yields, resistance occurrence and management.</p><p> </p><p>This work has been taken forward by ADAS on behalf of the National Farmers’ Union. Their interim evidence (excluding the crop yield data which will not be available until after this year’s harvest) formed part of the evidence considered by the UK Expert Committee on Pesticides in respect of the 2016 applications and will be reflected in their detailed record of the discussion at their 4 May meeting. The report will not be finalised until yield data is available after harvest.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-09T15:54:24.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517161/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517161/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-03","Oilseed Rape: Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the results collected to date by the study conducted for her Department by ADAS on neonicotinoid treated and non-neonicotinoid treated oilseed rape prior to any further emergency authorisation applications related to the use of neonicotinoids","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","36286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517162","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Rural Payments Agency has regular discussions with the Welsh Government and they are working together to get Basic Payment Scheme claims paid to cross-border farmers.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-09T10:30:10.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517162/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517162/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-03","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Rural Payments Agency and the Welsh Government on delays in paying Basic Payments Scheme cheques to cross-border farmers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","36388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517164","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>I have no plans to raise this case with the Chinese Government. We have a regular dialogue with the Chinese about the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), which covers the effective implementation of UN sanctions to prevent North Korea from developing nuclear weapons, and encouraging China to confront human rights violations by the North Korean regime, most notably the important principle of non-refoulement. I raised both points with Chinese Vice Minister Chen Fengxiang in December.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-09T14:28:43.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517164/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517164/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","China: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will raise the murder of the Korean-Chinese pastor Han Choong Yeol on 30 April 2016 in China with his Chinese counterpart; and if he will request that his Chinese counterpart investigate whether the North Korean security services were involved in that murder.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","36385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517165","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>We are aware of the Algerian investigation of two Protestant house churches in the north eastern area of Algeria, known as the Kabylie, in January 2016. We understand that the issue has been resolved and that the churches continue to conduct their business.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T13:39:57.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517165/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517165/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Algeria: Churches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will raise with his Algerian counterpart threats of legal proceedings being instituted against a church in the North Eastern province of that country for conducting religious services.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","36386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517166","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-09","<p>Those entering the Sovereign Base Areas (SBA) including the two crossing points from north Cyprus are subject to immigration checks conducted by SBA Customs and Immigration personnel to confirm their identity, nationality and permissibility to enter the SBA. These border crossings are recognised points of entry into the EU. This process is consistent with the current procedures used in the Republic of Cyprus. No border control exists between the SBA and the Republic of Cyprus.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-09T15:22:22.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517166/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517166/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-03","Cyprus: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the border policy is for the Sovereign Base Areas.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","36360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517167","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>Any vessel registered in the UK, an Overseas Territory or a Crown Dependency, is a ‘British ship’ and is entitled to fly the British Merchant Shipping flag (the 'Red Ensign'). The UK remains the flag State for all ships flying the Red Ensign and is ultimately responsible under international law for these ships. The UK has general superintendence over the ship registers in the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies. This general superintendence derives from the UK’s obligations under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea regarding ships flying its flag; these obligations have been implemented in domestic legislation.</p><p>Under prerogative powers all British flagged vessels (including those on UK Overseas Territories and Crown Dependency registers) can be requisitioned where there is deemed to be a threat to the realm. Conscription of all British flagged vessels is done by Government Order. Such Order is enacted only during national crisis, such as war. The decision to use such Order is decided on a case by case basis by the Government of the day. For example, this Order was enacted during the Falklands War.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-10T13:08:16.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517167/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517167/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","British Overseas Territories: Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, under what circumstances the Government can take ships up from trade which are registered with flags of British Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","36361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517168","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>This Government shares the House of Common’s condemnation of Daesh atrocities against minorities, and the majority Muslim populations of Iraq and Syria. The Prime Minister, the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) has said he believes there is a very strong case to answer, but ultimately it should be a matter for judicial authorities.</p><p>We will do all we can to support the gathering and preservation of evidence that could in future be used in a court to hold Daesh to account. And we are continuing to deliver our comprehensive strategy to defeat Daesh and thereby stop them from preventing more atrocities. Addition as per PQ 35349.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:35:50.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517168/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517168/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Islamic State: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the decision of the House of 20 April 2016, on recognition of genocide by Daesh against Yazidis, Christians and other religious minorities, what steps he is taking to implement that resolution.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","36383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517169","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>We continue to follow the political situation in Brazil closely. The impeachment process is a matter for the people of Brazil and their elected representatives. We believe that the Brazilian people and their institutions will resolve the matter in a democratic way and in accordance with their Constitution.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-09T14:09:01.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517169/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517169/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Brazil: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the legitimacy of the impeachment process of President Dilma Rousseff in Brazil.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","36384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517170","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>In August 2014, the UK sponsored UN Security Council resolution 2170 which reaffirmed the call for those who have committed or are responsible for violations of international humanitarian law in Iraq and Syria to be held accountable. UN Security Council resolution 2249, passed in November 2015, confirmed the importance of holding the Islamic State in the Levant (also known as Daesh) to account. These resolutions follow an attempt in May 2014 to have the Security Council refer the situation in Syria to the International Criminal Court which was vetoed by Russia and China.</p><p>We continue to discuss with partners on the UN Security Council further ways to ensure that the perpetrators of crimes committed in Syria and Iraq are held to account and face justice. We will do all we can to support gathering and preservation of evidence that could in future be used in a court to hold Daesh to account. Addition as per PQ 35349.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:32:36.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517170/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517170/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Islamic State: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to refer to the UN Security Council the evidence being collected by his Department on potential acts of genocide committed by Daesh.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","36271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517171","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK Government is not directly involved in the preservation of cultural sites in Sudan. However, the British Council has previously sought to increase the awareness and appreciation of Sudan’s cultural heritage, including its cultural sites, amongst Sudanese youth. In addition, the British Museum has long-been involved in the archaeology of Sudan, including the preservation of cultural sites in Sudan, often with the support of the British Council.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-11T10:55:25.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517171/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517171/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Sudan: Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support the preservation of cultural sites in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","36255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517172","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>We have longstanding concerns about the new law, which we made clear to the Chinese authorities through an EU letter on 4 June 2015. We have also fully supported the EU’s other actions in expressing concern about the law, including various written representations and its Item 4 statement at the Human Rights Council in March. I set out our views to the Chinese Ambassador in June last year and we raised the matter at Ministerial level during the UK-China People-to-People Dialogue in September 2015. We fully support the recent EU statement of 4 May.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-09T14:09:53.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517172/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517172/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","China: Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the People's Republic of China on that government's proposed new law on control of foreign non-governmental organisations.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","36259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517173","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>I follow the human rights situation in China closely and the wider impact of legislative developments. We will be gathering reactions, in particular from UK organisations and British nationals working in the Non-Governmental Organisation sector, to assess the law’s potential impact ahead of it coming into force in January 2017. Along with EU partners we will be submitting detailed questions around the implementation of the law to the Chinese authorities.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-09T14:12:40.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517173/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517173/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","China: Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the potential effects of proposed legislation in China on the management of foreign non-governmental organisations' activities.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","36260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517174","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>It is not possible to refer Daesh itself to the ICC. Any referral would cover all potential crimes within a specified geographic area, rather than by a specified organisation or set of actors.</p><p>We judge that a referral to the International Criminal Court (ICC) by the UN Security Council is not practical at this time. When efforts were made to refer the situation in Syria to the ICC in 2014, it was vetoed by Russia and China.</p><p>While we continue to draw the attention of the Security Council to the atrocities being committed in Iraq and Syria - on 4 May the Council held a session on the situation in Aleppo at the UK’s request - we expect that any Security Council resolution at this time seeking to refer the situations in Iraq or Syria to the ICC would likewise be blocked. Addition as per PQs 36262 and 35349.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:50:47.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517174/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517174/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Islamic State: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to help create consensus at the UN Security Council for a referral to the International Criminal Court of the acts committed by Daesh in Iraq and Syria as genocide.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","36261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517175","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>It is not possible for the UN Security Council to refer Daesh itself to the International Criminal Court (ICC). Any referral would cover all potential crimes within a specified geographic area, rather than by a specified organisation or set of actors.</p><p>We would consider carefully any suggestion from another member of the Security Council to refer the situation in Iraq and Syria to the ICC.</p><p>However, we judge that a referral to the International Criminal Court by the UN Security Council is not practical at this time.</p><p>When efforts were made to refer the situation in Syria to the ICC in 2014, it was vetoed by Russia and China. We expect that any Security Council resolution at this time seeking to refer the situations in Iraq or Syria to the ICC would likewise be blocked.</p><p>We continue to discuss with partners on the UN Security Council further ways to ensure that the perpetrators of crimes committed in Syria and Iraq are held to account and face justice.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-05-09T15:54:10.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517175/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517175/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Islamic State: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on voting in favour of referring as genocide the acts committed by Daesh in Iraq and Syria to the International Criminal Court in the event of another member of the UN Security Council proposing such a referral.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","36262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517176","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-06","<p>The Forced Marriage Unit is a joint Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Home Office Unit which was set up in January 2005 to lead on the Government's forced marriage policy, outreach and casework. Statistics on the number of enquiries and cases dealt with by the Forced Marriage Unit via its public helpline and email inbox in 2013, 2014 and 2015 are published online here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-05-06T13:36:22.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517176/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517176/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Forced Marriage Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people made contact with the Forced Marriage Unit in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","36315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517177","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","There have been no discussions between the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Russian Ambassador about Mr Bukovsky’s health.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-05-11T09:16:00.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517177/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517177/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Vladimir Bukovsky","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the Russian Ambassador on the health of Vladimir Bukovsky; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","36252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517178","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given by my Rt Hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office today to UIN: 36288.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-05-11T15:31:01.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517178/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517178/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517179","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-09","Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials transferred the letter from the hon. Member for Leeds Central to UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI), part of the Home Office, on 18 September 2015. UKVI responded to the letter on 1 October 2015. All government departments endeavour to provide comprehensive responses to all correspondence from Members of this House. However, I understand that on this occasion the response did not satisfactorily address all of the issues raised in your letter. Officials at the Home Office have assured me that they will be providing a further reply to your letter, addressing these points, by the end of this week.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-09T13:33:49.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517179/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517179/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-03","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects the British High Commission in Barbados to respond to the email of 10 September 2015 from the right hon. Member for Leeds Central regarding Mr Rawlins.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","36282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517180","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Targeted Enhanced Recruitment Scheme has been set up by Health Education England (HEE) and NHS England as a one year pilot scheme to support recruitment of general practitioner trainees in the 109 training places in England that have been hard to recruit to for the past three years.</p><p> </p><p>Recruitment is currently ongoing and 2016 fill rates will be published on the HEE website once recruitment has closed.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T11:30:49.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517180/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517180/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","General Practitioners: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many bursaries have been offered (a) in total and (b) in each of the seven most hard to recruit areas as part of NHS England's Targeted Enhanced Recruitment Scheme in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Matt Warman","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","36319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517181","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>I responded to the hon. Member’s letter of 4 April on 29 April.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-09T10:56:57.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517181/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517181/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to reply to the letter of 4 April 2016 from the hon. Member for Walsall North regarding the Manor Hospital, Walsall.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","36276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517182","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by the Minister of State for the Cabinet Office on 11 May to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-05-03/36288/" target="_blank">36288</a>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-11T15:35:20.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517182/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517182/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Department of Health: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department and its agencies and non-departmental public bodies have spent on infraction proceedings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517183","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>NHS England has advised that Avastin is currently funded through the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) for three indications, all of which are off-label. It is also in the process of reviewing and setting up a system for assessing off-label drug indications. Each of the three off-label indications for Avastin will remain funded within the CDF until they have been assessed through the new process.</p><p> </p><p>Clinicians can prescribe any treatment, including an unlicensed product or a product not licensed for a particular indication, which they consider the best available medicine to meet the individual clinical needs of their patient, subject to their primary care organisation agreeing to fund this treatment.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) produces Evidence Summaries which critically review the best available evidence for significant uses of unlicensed or off-label medicines. They help commissioners and clinicians to make evidence-based prioritisation, treatment and funding decisions where there are no clinically-appropriate licensed alternatives.</p><p> </p><p>Ensuring that patients get timely access to any new treatment, including off-label medicines in new indications, is complex and the Department is committed to working with stakeholders including NICE, the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency, the General Medical Council, patient and professional groups, and charities to co-ordinate activities and set plans in place that will make this easier. This includes work to look at more systematic inclusion of off-label uses of drugs in the British National Formulary and development of case studies looking at re-purposed medicines and their pathways from research results into clinical practice.</p><p>Alongside these, the Access to Medical Treatments (Innovation) Act will, in due course, provide the National Health Service with a newly created database which will provide a mechanism for collecting and sharing information on innovative treatments including off-label drugs and medicines in development. Now that the Act has received Royal Assent the work to implement its provisions can begin.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-11T08:22:27.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517183/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517183/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the effect of proposed reforms to the Cancer Drugs Fund on the provision in the NHS of (a) Avastin and (b) other drugs currently approved for off-licence use.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","36254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517184","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>This information is not held centrally. Amounts paid to Board members engaged off-payroll are disclosed in individual annual reports of National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts but amounts paid to other off-payroll workers within the scope of the HM Treasury guidance cannot be separately identified.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-09T09:35:15.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517184/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517184/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","NHS: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 35252, what the total amount paid to off-payroll staff was by (a) NHS trusts in 2014-15 and (b) NHS foundation trusts in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","36334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517185","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>The policy statement for the commissioning of Everolimus for treating angiomyolipomas has not yet been published owing to delays experienced when incorporating the needs of children into the policy.</p><p>Those issues have now been resolved and the policy is due to be published imminently on NHS England’s website.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-09T09:19:42.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517185/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517185/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 29900, on tuberous sclerosis, for what reasons the policy statement for the commissioning of Everolimus for treating angiomyolipomas has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish that statement.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","36339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517186","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Care Quality Commission’s Chief Inspector of Hospitals, Professor Sir Mike Richards, and the Chief Executive of NHS Improvement, Jim Mackey, decided jointly upon the recommendation for a long-term partnership between Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust and The Ipswich Hospital NHS Trust. A merger has not been announced.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has regular conversations with NHS Improvement and the Care Quality Commission about trusts in special measures such as Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust. I also spoke with the Chair and Chief Executive of Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust, scheduled at their request, on 15 March 2016.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-09T14:29:35.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517186/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517186/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Colchester Hospital: Ipswich Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department had with (a) Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust, (b) NHS Improvement and (c) the Care Quality Commission, prior to the announced merger of Colchester General Hospital and Ipswich Hospital.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","36274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517187","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>This is a matter for the Department for Education (DfE).</p><p>Schools can play an important role in supporting pupils with mental health issues. We want them to decide how best to meet the needs of their pupils. DfE has taken a range of actions to help them build a whole-school approach to good mental wellbeing, including the recently revised and updated blueprint for effective school-based counselling. This provides practical, evidence-based advice, informed by experts on how to ensure school based counselling services achieve the best outcomes for all students, including vulnerable children and young people. The weblink to the guidance, <em>Counselling in schools: a blueprint for the future - Departmental advice for school leaders and counsellors</em> is:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/counselling-in-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/counselling-in-schools</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-09T09:18:40.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517187/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517187/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Schools: Counselling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps with the Department of Education to introduce a counselling strategy for schools.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","36267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517188","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>The total cost of the current contract for the National Diet and Nutrition Survey (NDNS), covering four years of fieldwork from 2013/14 to 2016/17 and including analysis and reporting, is £15.4 million.</p><p>The most recent NDNS report, covering diet, nutrient intake and nutritional status in United Kingdom adults and children, was published in May 2014. This report was based on data collected under the previous contract for NDNS covering fieldwork from 2008/09 to 2011/12.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-09T15:09:15.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517188/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517188/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Nutrition: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse is of provision of the National Diet and Nutrition Survey; and for what reasons an updated survey has not been published since 2012.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","36268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517189","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department has taken steps to increase public awareness of all rare diseases including conditions such as Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, through the implementation of the UK Strategy for Rare Diseases. The Strategy includes specific commitments to raise awareness of rare diseases.</p><p> </p><p>The Strategy is currently being implemented across all four countries of the United Kingdom with progress monitored by the UK Rare Disease Forum. The first progress report by the Forum was published in February 2016.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-11T08:23:27.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517189/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517189/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to raise awareness of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","36243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517190","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Department does not collect this information. Rota arrangements for junior doctors are a matter for individual National Health Service foundation trusts.</p><p>Contact details for NHS foundation trusts and all other NHS authorities can be found on the NHS Choices website:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/nhsengland/thenhs/about/pages/authoritiesandtrusts.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.nhs.uk/nhsengland/thenhs/about/pages/authoritiesandtrusts.aspx</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-05-10T11:30:11.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517190/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517190/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Junior Doctors: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average rota gap is for junior doctors in NHS foundation trusts in the most recent period for which figures are available; and what assessment he has made of the effect on services of the size of that gap.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","36230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517191","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is producing a liver disease framework which will outline PHE’s wide range of work contributing to the prevention of liver disease and improved wellbeing for patients with liver disease. PHE is working closely with NHS England, The Lancet Commission and liver disease charities to support improvements in the quality of care for liver disease patients through the provision of information to support decision making.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-09T14:11:14.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517191/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517191/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Liver Diseases: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions officials of his Department have had with external bodies on the development of a national liver strategy or liver framework; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","36231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517192","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>The appointment of national clinical directors (NCDs) is a matter for NHS England. It has recently reviewed these roles and is now supported by 18 NCDs, although there is no specific NCD for liver disease. However, NHS England advises that clinical advice relating to gastrointestinal and liver disease will be sought from a variety of sources, including: experts at Public Health England for alcohol related issues; the NCD for obesity and diabetes for issues relating to obesity induced fatty liver disease; and through the Clinical Reference Group for Hepatitis C and the Medical Royal Colleges.</p><p>The full list of NCDs can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/about/whos-who/ncd/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/about/whos-who/ncd/</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-09T14:12:18.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517192/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517192/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Liver Diseases: National Clinical Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions officials of his Department have had with external bodies on reintroducing a national clinical director for liver disease.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","36232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517193","Home Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>An impact assessment of a minimum unit price for alcohol was published before a consultation on the Government's Alcohol Strategy proposals in 2012.</p><p>The consultation raised questions concerning possible unintended consequences of minimum unit pricing, such as the impact on responsible drinkers on low incomes. The Government continues to monitor the research being carried out by the University of Sheffield and others on the potential effects.</p><p>The Government has also noted the ruling of the Court of Justice of the European Union on the proposed introduction of minimum unit pricing in Scotland and will continue to monitor the legal proceedings.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-05-09T15:16:47.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517193/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517193/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-03","Alcoholic Drinks: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of introducing a minimum unit price for alcohol.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","36233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517194","Department of Health","false","2016-05-09","<p>The next report of the National Diet and Nutrition Survey is being prepared and will be published as an Official Statistic; the publication date will be announced in advance in accordance with the Official Statistics Code of Practice.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-09T14:07:42.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517194/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517194/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Nutrition: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the next set of National Diet and Nutrition Survey data will be published.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","36359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517195","Department of Health","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Childhood Obesity Strategy will draw from a range of the latest data and evidence, including from Public Health England and other partners.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","36357","2016-05-10T16:23:17.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517195/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517195/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-03","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether data other than the most recent National Diet and Nutrition Survey data is being used in the development of the childhood obesity strategy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","36356"
